Announcement of a new Contest;

Name:          The Sub-Nomic Contest  (Or: how recursive can we get?)
Contestmaster: Swann



    Contestmaster note:
    This is based on Suber's Initial Set as it appeared Hofstader's book 
    _Meta-Magical Themas_.  I have modified it as little as possible,
    adding the category of Unmutable Regulations (Which are there to
    interface between Daddy Nomic and Baby Nomic, and are defined as
    unchangeable and of absolute precedence-- in the Immutable and Mutable
    Regulations :)

    Any Reg with an asterisk after it has been modified slightly from
    the text of the book, generally to take the e-mail form of the game,
    or the nature of running this as a Contest in the context of a
    larger game, into account.

    I didn't asterisk changes that were simply terminology, which
    amount to the following:

    Regulations = Rules
    Contestants = Players
    Credits     = Points
    Contest     = Game

    (Sorry, there was no elegant way to rename voters and judges)

    Other potential terminology conflicts are dealt with by unmutable
    002.  (Also note the capitalization, or lack thereof, which is to
    further avoid confusion with the larger game.)

O. Unmutable Regulations

000* This contest is a sub-game of Agora Nomic and contestants must
     abide by all rules of Agora in effect.  Any regulation of this
     contest that is inconsistent with the rules of Agora Nomic is also
     void within the Sub-Nomic contest.

001* The entry fee of this contest shall be 5 points.

002* Whenever a term appears in the regulations that ambiguously could
     refer either to Agora Nomic or to Sub-Nomic, the term refers to
     Sub-Nomic.

003* Whenever the regulations state that a contestant has won the
     contest, that player becomes the contestmaster, if e consents.
     If e doesn't consent, the consenting contestant with the highest
     number of credits becomes the new contestmaster.  In case of a tie,
     the old contestmaster chooses a winner and new contestmaster.  When
     a new contestmaster is chosen, the old contestmaster becomes a
     contestant.

004* When a new contest begins, play continues with the regulations then
     in effect.

005* When a new contestmaster is selected, e receives the entire
     contents of the contest fund.  This is the only funds transfer
     allowed out of the contest fund.  After this transfer, no funds may
     be transferred out of the contest fund until a new contestmaster is
     again selected.

006* Whenever a new contest begins, and after the new contestmaster has
     received eis reward out of the contest fund, all contestants must
     put five points (or any currency the new contestmaster deems an
     acceptable substitute) into the contest fund.

007* The contestmaster must post all regulation changes to the public
     forum within 48 hours after the contestants' votes are tabulated,
     and no later than one week after the voting period has closed.

008* The contestmaster must accept any and all transfers into the
     contest fund, from whatever source.

I. Immutable Regulations

101*  All Contestants must always abide by all the Regulations then in
      effect, in the form in which they are then in effect.  The
      Regulations in the Initial Set are in effect whenever a contest
      begins.  The Initial set consists of regulations 000-008
      (unmutable), 101-116 (immutable), and 201-213 (mutable).

102.  Initially, regulations in the 100's are immutable and regulations
      in the 200's are mutable.  Regulations subsequently enacted or
      transmuted (i.e. changed from immutable to mutable or vice versa)
      may be mutable or immutable regardless of their numbers, and all
      non-unmutable regulations in the Initial Set may be transmuted
      regardless of their numbers.  Unmutable regulations may not be
      transmuted.

103*  A regulation change is any of the following:
      
        i) The enactment, amendment, or repeal of a mutable regulation.
       ii) The enactment, amendment, or repeal of an amendment.
      iii) The transmutation of a immutable regulation into a mutable
           regulation or vice versa.
      
      No regulation change may affect an unmutable regulation.

104.  All regulation changes proposed in the proper way shall be voted
      on. They will be adopted if and only if they receive the required 
      number of votes.

105.  Every contestant in this contest is an eligible voter.  Every
      eligible voter must participate in every vote on regulation
      changes.

106*  Any proposed regulation change must be written down and submitted
      to the Contestmaster before it is voted upon.  If adopted, it must
      guide play in the form in which it was voted on.

107.  No regulation change may take effect earlier than the moment of
      the completion of the vote that adopted it, even if its wording
      explicitly states otherwise.  No regulation change may have
      retroactive application.

108*  The contestmaster shall give each proposed regulation change an
      ordinal number for reference.  The numbers shall begin with 301,
      and each regulation change proposed in the proper way shall
      receive the next successive integer, whether or not the proposal
      is adopted.

      If a regulation is repealed and re-enacted, it receives the number 
      of the proposal to re-enact it.  If a regulation is amended or
      transmuted, it receives the ordinal number of the proposal to
      amend or transmute it.  If an amendment is amended or repealed,
      the entire regulation of which it is a part receives the ordinal
      number of the proposal to amend or repeal the amendment.

109.  Regulation changes that transmute immutable regulations into
      mutable regulations may be adopted if and only if the vote is
      unanimous among all eligible voters.

110* Mutable regulations that are inconsistent in any way with some
     immutable regulation (except by proposing to transmute it) are
     wholly void and without effect.  They do not implicitly transmute
     immutable regulations into mutable regulations and at the same time
     amend them.  Regulation changes that transmute immutable
     regulations into mutable regulations will be effective if and only
     if they explicitly state their transmuting effect.

     Regulations in conflict with any unmutable regulations are wholly
     void and without effect.

111* If a regulation change as proposed is unclear, ambiguous,
     paradoxical, or destructive of play, or if it arguably consists of
     two or more regulation changes compounded, or is an amendment that
     makes no difference, of if it is otherwise of questionable value,
     then the other players may debate against the proposal before the
     vote. One week is allowed for this debate, from the time the
     contestmaster submits the proposal to all contestants, after which
     time the vote is taken.

112. The state of affairs that constitutes winning may not be changed
     from the achieving N credits to any other state of affairs.
     However, the magnitude of N and the means of earning credits my be
     changed, and the regulations that establish a winner when play
     cannot continue may be enacted and (while they are mutable) be
     amended or repealed.

113. A contestant always has the option to forfeit the contest rather
     than continue to play or incur a penalty.  No penalty, worse than
     losing, in the judgment of the player to incur it, may be imposed.

114. There must always be at least one mutable regulation.  The adoption
     of regulation changes must never become completely impermissible.

115. Regulations that affect regulations needed to allow or apply
     regulation changes are as permissible as other regulation changes.
     Even regulation changes that amend or repeal their own authority
     are permissible.  No regulation change or type of move is
     impermissible solely on account of the self-reference or
     self-application of a regulation.

116. Whatever is not explicitly prohibited or regulated by a regulation
     is permitted and unregulated, with the sole exception of changing
     the regulations, which is permitted only when a regulation or set
     of regulations explicitly or implicitly permits it.

II. Mutable Regulations

201* All contestants begin a new contest with exactly zero credits.

202* Contestants may propose regulation changes by submitting them to
     the contestmaster, who must then distribute the proposed change to
     all contestants for debate.  The contestmaster must submit all
     properly-submitted proposals within a week of receiving them.

203. A regulation change is adopted if and only if the vote is unanimous
     among the eligible voters.

204. If and when rule changes can be adopted without unanimity, the
     contestants who vote against winning proposals shall receive 10
     credits apiece.

205. An adopted regulation change takes full effect at the moment of the
     completion of the vote that adopted it.

206. When a proposed regulation change is defeated the contestant who
     proposed it loses 10 credits.

207. Each contestant has exactly one vote.

208. The winner is the first contestant to achieve 100 (positive)
     credits.

209. At no time may there be more than 25 mutable regulations.

210. Contestants may not conspire or consult on the making of future
     rule changes unless they are teammates.

211* If two or more mutable regulations conflict with one another, or if
     two or more immutable regulations conflict with one another, or if
     two or more unmutable regulations conflict with one another, then
     the regulation with the lowest ordinal number takes precedence.

     Unmutable regulations take precidence over all other regulations.
     Immutable regulations take precidence over all mutable regulations.

     If at least one of the regulations in conflict explicitly says of
     itself that it defers to another regulation (or type of regulation)
     or takes precedence over another regulation (or type of
     regulation), then such provisions shall supersede the numerical
     method for determining precedence.

     If two or more regulations claim to take precedence over each
     other, or to defer to one another, then the numerical method must
     again govern.

212* If contestants disagree about the legality of a move or the
     interpretation or application of a regulation, then the
     contestmaster must chose a contestant other than the contestant
     alleging the illegal move, or the contestant who allegedly made
     the illegal move, and appoint that contestant as judge.  That
     contestant must then decide the question.  Disagreement, for the
     purposes of this rule, may be created by the insistence of any
     contestant.  Such a process is called "invoking judgment."

     The selected judge has one week to render an opinion.  If the judge
     does not, the contestmaster may rule on the issue eimself.

     The judge's judgment may be overruled only by unanimous vote of
     the other contestants.  Such overturning must be in a proposal sent
     to the contestmaster, and voted upon in the same way as proposed
     regulation changes.  If such a proposal passes, the contestmaster
     chooses a new judge in the same manner as before, with the same
     restrictions.  No contestant may judge the same question twice. If
     there are no remaining eligible contestants to serve as judge, the
     contestmaster must decide the question.

     If the contestmaster issues a judgment, the ruling is final.

     All judgments must be written and submitted to the contestmaster,
     who must distribute them to all contestants within a week.

     New judges are not bound by the decisions of old judges.  New
     judges may, however, settle only that question which e was assigned
     to judge.  All judgments by judges shall be in accordance to the
     regulations then in affect; but when the regulations are silent;
     inconsistent, or unclear on the point at issue, then the judge's
     only guides shall be common morality, common logic, and the spirit
     of the contest.

213* If the regulations are changed so that further play is impossible,
     or if the legality of a move is impossible to determine with
     finality, or if by the judge's best reasoning, not overruled, a
     move appears equally legal or illegal, then the player with the
     most credits wins.  This regulation takes precedence over every
     other rule determining who wins this contest.



