Blob enters the discussion:
> Steve said:
>   
>> If I were starting a new game now
>> with, say, Suber's Initial Ruleset, I'd find it very hard not to apply the
>> lessons I've learned here about how to deal with those problems effectively.
> 
>How much would it take, in your estimation, to "fix" Suber's initial set
>without adding any extra functionality? 
>
>I know this is a vague question - any change is essentially new functionality,
>but I think you understand what I mean. 

This is a good question. Who knows, perhaps I'll join Swann's sub-Nomic 
and find out...

My take on this question is that that Suber's Initial Ruleset contains 
a series of built-in crises which must be faced. Certainly requiring 
unanimous consent for each Rule Change is the first crisis; this will 
only be overcome if the players understand that there is no game otherwise.
Immediately afterwards comes the reward for voting against proposals 
which succeed.

So "fixing" the Suber Initial Set means, for starters, replacing these
two rules.  I do _not_ say that the initial set should be different;
rather, that players in a new Nomic could reasonably focus on how to 
change these. In fact, a flawed Initial Ruleset might be a necessary 
condition for a good game!

I also do not count things necessary to adapt Suber's rules for continuous
e-mail play, for example abandoning the "taking turns" structure, or 
continuing the Game and Ruleset after a win.

Some of the lessons learned in Nomic World and Agora would be valuable 
to incorporate.  These include the following:

1. Some current rules in force in Agora represent hard lessons learned,
   like forbidding a Proposal from rewarding or penalizing on the basis
   of votes cast for that proposal.

   I'm more ambivalent about the "no coerced vote" rule.  Some ways of 
   wording this Rule would have prevented the Group Ordinances from 
   enforcing party discipline.  This might or might not be a good thing, 
   but I'm glad we've had the opportunity to experiment with it, at least 
   in the Reform and X groups.

2. Immutable reform was a way of making the game more flexible.  With 
   no Immutable rules it is possible to completely change the game.

   I doubt that we need the infinitely many levels possible under the
   present system; probably two levels of "Mutable" and "Less Mutable"
   would be sufficient.

3. In Suber's initial set, a rule is renumbered every time it is amended.
   This usually causes it to lose precedence under the conflict rule.
   (Another built-in crisis. Deliberate?)  Our present scheme is one 
   way of fixing this.

4. Our whole scheme of Judgement and Appeals is a fairly stable and 
   consistent one.  From what Steve has said, it was arrived at after
   much experimentation and is the best one he's seen in this game's
   history.  The fact that it has not changed substantially in the
   8 months I've been here is some testimony to its value.  We've 
   consistently resisted Appeal by Proposal, because historically a 
   fair number of the CFJ's involve the Proposal rules themselves!

   Already in Nomic World (see Lindrum's Judgement), the players saw 
   the value of restricting judgement to TRUE, FALSE, and UNDECIDED, 
   rather than allow unbridled judicial activism.

5. Every Nomic has its version of Rule 116 (Permissibility of the 
   Unprohibited).  Agora has Rule 1011 (Game Entities May Not Be 
   Arbitrarily Changed).  Somthing whose value is evident to anyone
   who's been here for a while!  (see the CFJ archives)

None of these involve extra "functionality" except perhaps the Court 
of Appeals.  Killing Immutables and creating "Less Mutables" is a trade
rather than an addition.

Having pointed out all these, I would note that there are things which 
have grown up historically and don't seem to be crucial.

For example, the distinction between "Proposals" and "proposed Rule 
Changes" grew up because the Gamestate includes more than the Rules.
However, it's not logically necessary to maintain a distinction.  
Pieces of the Gamestate like Offices or Patent Titles could perfectly 
well be kept within the Ruleset, and awarding a Patent Title or Office 
could just be another Rule Creation or Amendment.

One other thing that's _not_ part of Agora:  Several other Nomics have 
a rule that goes something like  "No proposal that identifies a Player 
by personal characteristic shall take effect unless that Player consents."
Something to consider, certainly, before removing the unanimous voting 
requirement.

Regards,
- elJefe

******************************************************************
  Dr. Jeffrey L. Caruso, B.N. <jlc@triple-i.com>
  Information International

