Chuck sez:
> What's all this sudden posting of proposals?  Have we completely dropped
> the idea of protoproposals?

I wanted my Proposal to get in the same round of distribution as those
proposing to remove the Ambassador.

> >Initial Set of Rules for InterNomic
> >by Don "Vanyel" Blaheta
> 
> I have quite a few problems with this initial set.  I think InterNomic
> is sufficiently different from Nomic that more than just an
> adaptation of the Agoran Initial Rules is needed as an initial Ruleset.

Why?  I thought that was the point of an Inter-Nomic!

> One of the problems I think you will find with this and many proposed
> Nomics is the loss of sovreignty of the individual Nomics.  For
> this reason, I think Nomics would be reluctant to join.  The InterNomic
> I envision, at the start, would *not* have sovreignty over the Member
> Nomics, but rather over individual players.  One of the interesting
> questions, IMO, is whether InterNomic can then establish sovreignty
> over the Member Nomics.

Well, participation in a game implies a loss of sovereignty.  Period.  I
mean, I have less "sovereignty" over my own life now--I have to (well, I
don't *have* to, but you know) log in fairly frequently to check mail
and vote and so on.  I also have yielded some control over my disk
quotas; rather a lot of space is taken up by the Archives.  Not that I
am doing this unwillingly, but I am yielding "sovereignty" to
participate in this Nomic.  I expect the same of participant Nomics.  In
any case, I never once visualized Internomic as just another Nomic whose
members happen to be all the members of all the subsidiary Nomics,
because that's all it would be--just another Nomic.

> I've already given a fair amount of thought to this, although I haven't
> written anything up yet.  Give me about a week and I'll show you what
> I envision as an Initial InterNomic Ruleset.

So've I.  And I've catalyzed the discussion, if nothing else. Go for it.

> Chuck

Vanyel

