Steve sez:
> Of course, to be useful in that way, you have to have access
> to the points when you need them. So Marks lost their utility
> for this purpose when Marks to points conversion was repealed
> (which explains the proliferation of the other methods). But 
> bringing back Marks conversion basically means having two
> identical Currencies floating about, the only difference being
> that Marks are not reset at game's end. And that seems an
> unnecessary duplication of Rules.

Marks don't lose their utility if they have value in and of themselves,
in addition to any storehouse capabilities.

> So what to do? Some options:
> 
> 1. Stop resetting points at game's end! Radical, but with the
> advantage of conceptual simplicity. Probably unpopular, though.
> Would have a number of far-reaching consequences.

No way.  A tad too radical.

> 2. Repeal Marks. If Players want to keep their points over game 
> ends, they can use some of the other Entities, like Kelly's Point
> Storehouse Contest Fund.

If all you want is storehouse stuff, I would just as soon have one
centralized, ruleset-sanctioned method of doing so--such as Marks.
Rather than everybody having a Group, or a Contest, or something else to
store their Points.

> 3. Bring back Marks conversion, and live with the duplication.
> After all, we've been living with it for quite a while anyway.

Boorrrring.  (But better than 2)

> 4. Don't bring back Marks conversion, but transact more of the
> game's business directly in Marks. This seems to be the option
> Kelly favours. It has the disadvantage that, to work really
> well, a huge number of Rules currently referring to points
> should really be amended to refer to Marks instead. 

This is my favourite.  "Huge number" is debatable... see below.

> Personally, I'm wavering between options (2) and (3) (and I'm 
> intrigued by (1), and am thinking about it some more). Despite
> saying earlier that I want to see Marks revived, on reflection
> I must say that I think (2) looks quite attractive.

Again, I dislike 2 almost as much as I dislike 1.

> Did I miss anything substantial?

Think about this.  I went through the Ruleset looking for all instances
of point awards and penalties:

SALARIES:
1007:X +3 Default
1036:X +3 Promotor
1449:X +5 Assessor
 889:X +5 CotC
 502:X +3 Judge
1051:X +5 Rulekeepor
 417:X +5 Archivist
 901:X +5 Scorekeepor
1436:X +4 Tabulator
1070:X +2 Ambassador
1458:X +3 Notary

PROPOSAL RELATED STUFF:
1061:  +5 New Player Bonus
 659:  -2 Long Proposal
       +1 Short Proposal
       -2 Wide Proposal
1065:  -1 Extra Proposal Fee
1451:  -5 Disowning Fee
 312:X +1 Point for Voting
1443:X +2 Proto Bonus
 833:XF-A Proposal Bonus/Penalty
 947:  +5 Repeal Bonus

JUDICIARY:
1431:  -5 Penalty for Denying a COE later CFJed & TRUE
 951:  -2 Declining a CFJ
1005:  -2 Penalty for going On Hold when assigned a CFJ
 502:  +2 Speedy judgement of CFJ
1448: -10 Penalty for defaulting as Justice

SPEAKER:
 785: -2N Abandoned Speaker
 681: -10 Speaker Transfer
1375: -2N Speaker On Hold
 942:  -T Psychotic Speaker

OTHER:
1023: -10 ASAP Penalty
1064: -10 FOIA Penalty
 840:  -1 Scamster Penalty
 726:Xavg New Player Initial Points
1034:X-25 Mark Purchase
1440:  -5 Blot erasure
1441:X-BL Start-of-Game Blot Penalty
1456: -50 Breach of Contract
1457:  -5 Frivolous Contract CFJ

The ones marked with "X"s are the ones I think should remain as Points;
the others either should become Marks Penalty/Bonuses, Either/or, or are
at least debatable.  In any case it probably wouldn't be all that
difficult to run up one big Proposal (I think it would even be MI=1)
that would make certain things Marks Penalties/Bonuses.

Certainly, anything that is a "Payment" instead of a "Penalty" should be
in Marks, except for the sole and obvious exception of purchasing Marks.

