Vlad sez:
> Not a bad simplification. Some questions:
> >  
> > Immutable Rules
> > 
> > 101.  All member nomics must always abide by all the rules then in
> >       effect, in the form in which they are then in effect.  At the
> 
> What, exactly, does this mean? Many of these rules would seem,
> by 101, to alter Agora's way of doing things, i.e. by defining
> how rules can be changed. Perhaps we need different terminology,
> perhaps some language about Nomics being free to regulate their
> own affairs, methods of government, etc.

Urk.  I had been referring to the modification of *internomic* rules;
iow, the methods used by each nomic would be internal to that nomic, at
least for the initial setup of internomic...

> > 102.  A nomic is a game in which the rules are changeable by those who
> >       play it.  The entities which play this nomic, aka "Internomic",
> >       are themselves nomics, aka "member nomics".  Every member nomic
> >       shall be either a voting member or a nonvoting member.  References
> >       in the rules to "nomics" or "members" shall mean member nomics,
> >       and shall include both voting and nonvoting members, unless
> >       otherwise noted.
> 
> Can people be members of more than one member Nomic? This might
> allow Agora to make many "Nomics" with the same players to stack
> voting. I don't see a good way around this.

See rule 216.  Yes, people can be in multiple nomics, but if one nomic
is largely a subsidiary of another, the smaller can't vote.  (Thus, the
FRC, of which Ronald, Andre, and I are also members, would be able to
vote, but Recursa couldn't.)

> > 103.  At any time, there shall be exactly one moderator.  The moderator
> >       must name a successor.  If the successor ceases to be a player or
> >       otherwise becomes ineligible to be moderator, the moderator shall
> >       appoint a new successor.  If the moderator ceases to be a player,
> >       the successor shall become moderator and must name a new
> >       successor.  The moderator and successor must be registered as
> >       players of at least one member nomic, and may not be liaisons.
>
> And what if he doesn't? No game penalties can equal the problems
> of not having a moderator. He can't even be replaced. Perhaps
> have a randomly selected Liason be the Successor.

Here I must just say that initially, at least, I will assume that
everybody will actually follow the rules.  A radical assumption, I know.

> > 105.  Every member nomic shall have a liaison at all times.  The liaison
> >       must be an entity registered as a player of that nomic.
> 
> Why the last sentence?

I suppose it isn't really necessary... but it does prevent nomics from
naming third parties as liaison.  Why they'd do that, I don't know...

> > Mutable rules
> > 
> > 201.  Quorum for a proposal is 20% of voting members at the beginning of
> >       the voting period for that proposal.
> 
> As you said to Chuck, why have Quorum? Also, 20% is too low. We may
> only have five Nomics (if that many) to start with.

Oops.  I meant to remove that.

> > 213.  Any nomic may submit a statement for judgement to the moderator.
> >       Upon receipt of such a statement, the moderator must randomly
> >       select a member to judge the statement.  The moderator must then
> >       distribute the statement and the identity of the judge to all
> >       member nomics.
> 
> No random selection?

Look at the second line.  "...must randomly select a member to
judge...."

> > 216.  If more than half the players of a member nomic are also players
> >       of a larger member nomic, the smaller nomic is a nonvoting member.
> 
> Concise. Perhaps too concise. There seem to be holes. How
> many potential members does this eliminate, anyway?

As far as I know, only recursa of the existing nomics, but it prevents a
bunch of people grouping into a separate nomic just for extra voting
power.  What it *doesn't* prevent is small groups from several nomics
getting together; of course, the voting dynamics of such a situation
would be so unique it is probably worth it not to bar them.

> Vlad

Vanyel

