Well, no I don't. Notice I only said I didn't *think* I'd allow it.
Perhaps I would. But I hope you'll concede at least that it's a grey
area. Consider a couple of examples not too far from Michael's 
(remember we're considering a hyopthetical 683 which requires the
Player to send eir votes to the Assessor). To which of the following
would argument above apply?

1. I decide I'm going to abstain on all Proposals just like Michael
does. But I can't write cron scripts. So, I get Michael to mail me
his script, and I just change the word "Michael" in the signature to
"Steve", leaving the message untouched. Then I run the program. In
that case, I didn't write the message or the script. Would I still be
sending my votes?

2. As above, but I'm even lazier. Instead of getting Michael to mail
me his script, I just ask him to make a duplicate of his script,
(again with the signature changed for convenience), which just runs
automatically whenever his original script does. Am I still sending
my votes? 

3. Someone objects to (2) above, saying that my votes don't come
from my address. Putting aside responses which note the problems
in deciding determinately what someone's address really is (given
that many of us often post from different machines), I ask Michael
modify his cron script for generating my votes so that it sends
my votes via 'my' machine. Does that make a difference?

4. I can no longer be bothered thinking about how to vote, so
I authorize Michael to modify the script he has which generates
my votes in any way he likes, eg so that I vote just like he
does. Now, am I still sending my votes?


Steve Gardner                     |  "Justice? You get justice in the next
Dept. of Philosophy, Monash Uni.  |   world, in this world you get the law."
gardner@aurora.cc.monash.edu.au   |          --  William Gaddis --

