From nomic-discussion-owner@teleport.com  Fri Aug 11 20:56:49 1995
Received: from desiree.teleport.com (desiree.teleport.com [192.108.254.11]) by Shamino.quincy.edu (8.6.12/8.6.9) with ESMTP id UAA14685 for <blahedo@quincy.edu>; Fri, 11 Aug 1995 20:56:44 -0500
Received: (from daemon@localhost) by desiree.teleport.com (8.6.10/8.6.9) id SAA16811 for nomic-discussion-outgoing; Fri, 11 Aug 1995 18:56:53 -0700
Received: from Shamino.quincy.edu (blahedo@Shamino.quincy.edu [192.217.45.2]) by desiree.teleport.com (8.6.10/8.6.9) with ESMTP id SAA16782 for <nomic-discussion@teleport.com>; Fri, 11 Aug 1995 18:56:47 -0700
Received: (from blahedo@localhost) by Shamino.quincy.edu (8.6.12/8.6.9) id UAA14676 for nomic-discussion@teleport.com; Fri, 11 Aug 1995 20:56:20 -0500
From: Don Blaheta <blahedo@quincy.edu>
Message-Id: <199508120156.UAA14676@Shamino.quincy.edu>
Subject: Re: A completely formal Nomic
To: nomic-discussion@teleport.com
Date: Fri, 11 Aug 1995 20:56:12 -0500 (CDT)
In-Reply-To: <199508111808.LAA27535@desiree.teleport.com> from "David M. Chess" at Aug 11, 95 02:01:11 pm
X-Mailer: ELM [version 2.4 PL24]
MIME-Version: 1.0
Content-Type: text/plain; charset=US-ASCII
Content-Transfer-Encoding: 7bit
Content-Length: 9076      
Sender: owner-nomic-discussion@teleport.com
Precedence: bulk
Reply-To: nomic-discussion@teleport.com
Status: RO

Favor sez:
> I was thinking about what a completely formal Nomic,
> without any of this stuff about word-meanings and the
> like, might be like.  I drafted a little tome, and
> I will take the liberty of posting it, in completely
> uncombed and unfinished form, here.  For random comments,
> and so anyone can tell me if anyone's already done
> something like this.  Also please feel free to
> complain to me if this is too far afield even for
> n-d.  I should probably take it to a.g.nomic.

Verrrry interesting.

> | favor |
 
> [. . .]
> 
> Details / Examples
> 
> The incoming interface is relatively simple: when a piece of mail
> comes in for the "server", it's parsed into one or more objects
> in the system.  Each object has a Type of "move", a Sender and
> Timestamp filled in from the envelope, a randomly-generated
> BatchNumber that's the same for all the objects created by the
> same piece of mail, and other fields filled in from the body
> of the message.  For instance, a request to register might
> look like:
> 
>    From: Matt Zimola <zimola@peeble.net>
>    Date: 14 Aug 1995, 12:36:13 UTC
>    Subject: to the Mech server
> 
>    REGISTER MattZ

An interface like this requires little more than a simple Perl script.
Good.

> and the corresponding object that gets created might be:
> 
>    ObjectNumber: 127
>    BatchNumber: 114
>    TimeStamp: 1995/08/14 12:36:13
>    Sender: zimola@peeble.net
>    Type: move
>    Subtype: register
>    RegisterName: MattZ

Not bad; as long as you make sure that every fieldname is unique.

> On the other end, various verbs that effect the existence and
> state of objects would cause extra-game side-effects to let the
> physical-world players know what's going on.  But these side-effects
> are not defined in or modifiable by the game rules; they are
> the Mechanism, not the Rules.

Right... a good point.

> A rule is just another object, with Type "rule", an "if"
> attribute which is some boolean function of the gamestate,
> and a "then" attribute which is some sequence of verbs.
> It also has a PrecendenceNumber, as well as various other
> housekeeping numbers.

Hmm... I'd implement that a bit differently... or perhaps just change
the "if-then" to "when-do", or something similar; however, selecting an
event-based system is definitely a good choice.  As for Precedence, you
might even rename it "Order", as the higher precedence rules would
evaluate first, and remove the ability of conflicting lower-precedence
rules to do so.

> The sequence of events in the game is as follows.  Note that
> this is again a thing that isn't part of, or changable by,
> the Rules, and this is another un-Nomic-like limitation.
> It may be possible to make some or all of this stuff adjustable
> within the game also; I haven't thought about that very hard
> yet.
> 
>   - Something happens: either a new object arrives from the
>     physical world via the incoming interface, or a new object
>     is created due to a schedule pop.

Hm.  As I visualize this, it could be done with a simple .forward file
which pipes incoming mail to the processor, and a cron table which sends
fakemail at the appropriate "schedule pop" times to the processor.

>   - For each object of Type "rule" in the gamestate, in order
>     of PrecedenceNumber, the value of the "if" attribute is
>     evaluated.  If the result if "false", we proceed to the
>     next "rule" object.  If the result is "true", the verbs in the
>     "then" attribute fire, creating or deleting or modifying or
>     scheduling objects; then we restart this "for" loop, back at
>     the rule with the highest (lowest-numbered) PrecendenceNumber.
>
>   - Once the lowest-precedence rule has had its "if" part
>     evaluate to "false", we go to sleep again until the next
>     thing happens.

Sounds slick.

> Here is a sample rule for creating a new player by registration,
> for instance:
> 
>    ObjectNumber: 7
>    PrecedenceNumber: 10
>    Type: rule
>    if: exists( Type==move, Subtype==register, RegisterName==%n,
>                Sender==%s, ObjectNumber==%o ) &
>        !exists( Type==player, Name==%n )
>    then: create ( Type==player, Name==%n, DefaultEmail==%s ) ;
>          destroy ( ObjectNumber==%o )

Hm.  I'm not too keen on your programming format, although I do agree it
should be kept really simple for the non-programmers out there.  I think
this would be a much easier/simpler/better way of doing the above:

  ObjectNumber: 7
  PrecedenceNumber: 10
  Type: rule
  When: Type == move,
        Subtype == register,
        RegisterName NOT IN Name
  Do: create ( Type: player,
               Name: RegisterName,
               Email: Sender )

Then, as each bit of mail comes in, queue up the queries contained
within, and send each individual query trickling down the ruleset; this
avoids assigning "temporary" objects.

> and the create verb, as well as creating an object with the given
> properties, would as an extra-game side effect notice that the
> type of the new object is player, and send a note back to the
> new player, welcoming em to the game.  Here's another:

No, since it is an extra-game effect, it would be done when the initial
"REGISTER" query were processed.

>    ObjectNumber: 7
>    PrecedenceNumber: 10
>    Type: rule
>    if: exists( Type==move, Subtype==register, RegisterName==%n,
>                Sender==%s, ObjectNumber==%o ) &
>        exists( Type==player, Name==%n )
>    then: create ( Type==failureNotice, To==%s,
>                   Text=="There is already a player by that name")
>          destroy ( ObjectNumber==%o )
> 
> with the obvious results.  There would also presumably be a low-precedence
> rule that simply destroys any failureNotice objects that exist, since
> their only purpose is to cause create() to do a side-effect.  That's
> sort of messy, and there may be some better way to do it.

Well, I wouldn't even put this in the gameset; this is another thing to
be handled in the "extra-game".

> Note that these rules explicitly destroy the object that caused them
> to fire.  This may not be a good idea in the general case, since
> other rules that fire after them won't have a chance to see the
> objects.  On the other hand, maybe it's correct, but the rules
> should also create a PlayerJustCreated object, or something, for
> others to notice and act on (and a cleanup rule at the end to
> destroy).  This seems a bit silly again, in that we have multiplying
> objects that don't represent any interesting rule-state, but are
> just used for inter-rule communication and side effects.  Is
> there some good way to avoid those?  Or would an "event" type
> of entity just be multiplying entity-types to no good purpose
> (since objects can in principle do it all)?

See, to start a query, the processor sets the appropriate variables (in
this case, Type, Subtype, RegisterName, and Sender), then starts the
query trickling through the rules.  Variables may be defined by rules
when they go into effect, or reset if the rule doesn't want
lower-precedence rules to take effect.  The rules keep running, of
course, until no rule intercepts the variables.

> Once points are invented, there might be a rule like this, the
> translation of "All players begin with zero points":
> 
>    ObjectNumber: 561
>    PrecedenceNumber: 20
>    Type: rule
>    if: exists( Type==player, Score=="", ObjectNumber==%o)
>    then: set ( ObjectNumber==%o ) (Score==0)
> 
> Note that the semantics are actually "If at any time a player
> has no defined score, that player's score shall be set to zero".

This particular rule might be better served by just setting the score
when the player is created.

> We still need to define the way rule-changing moves work, and
> a win condition.  The simplest form of the latter would be
> something like
> 
>    ObjectNumber: 14
>    PrecedenceNumber: 15
>    Type: rule
>    if: exists( Type==player, Score>99, ObjectNumber==%o)
>    then: wins ( %o )
> 
> where wins() would have very special side effects.  Note
> that this makes winning very atomic, since rules could not
> change what wins() does.  More flexibly:
> 
>    ObjectNumber: 14
>    PrecedenceNumber: 15
>    Type: rule
>    if: exists( Type==player, Score>99, ObjectNumber==%o)
>    then: create ( Type==victory, Winner==%o)
> 
> and other rules could make things happen to the victorious
> player, based on the existence of the victory object.

This would be better than the other way; more likely I would do the
following:

  ObjectNumber: 14
  PrecedenceNumber: 15
  Type: rule
  When: $t = exists( Type == player,
                     Score > 99 )
  Do: Win = true,
      Winner = $t

I use the $ to represent temporary variables, much like your %, but I
prefer $ because it means basically the same thing in perl.

Vanyel

-=-=-=-Don Blaheta-=-=-=-blahedo@quincy.edu-=-=-=-dblaheta@aol.com-=-=-=-

What is the difference between a Turing machine and the modern
computer?  It's the same as that between Hillary's ascent of Everest
and the establishment of a Hilton on its peak.

From nomic-discussion-owner@teleport.com  Fri Aug 11 21:53:41 1995
Received: from desiree.teleport.com (desiree.teleport.com [192.108.254.11]) by Shamino.quincy.edu (8.6.12/8.6.9) with ESMTP id VAA14910 for <blahedo@quincy.edu>; Fri, 11 Aug 1995 21:53:39 -0500
Received: (from daemon@localhost) by desiree.teleport.com (8.6.10/8.6.9) id TAA29302 for nomic-discussion-outgoing; Fri, 11 Aug 1995 19:46:46 -0700
Received: from becker1.u.washington.edu (gorgonne@becker1.u.washington.edu [140.142.12.67]) by desiree.teleport.com (8.6.10/8.6.9) with SMTP id TAA29294 for <nomic-discussion@teleport.com>; Fri, 11 Aug 1995 19:46:44 -0700
Received: by becker1.u.washington.edu
	(5.65+UW95.07/UW-NDC Revision: 2.33 ) id AA09220;
	Fri, 11 Aug 95 19:46:43 -0700
Date: Fri, 11 Aug 1995 19:46:42 -0700 (PDT)
From: Adrian Brown <gorgonne@becker.u.washington.edu>
X-Sender: gorgonne@becker1.u.washington.edu
To: nomic-discussion@teleport.com
Subject: Re: A completely formal Nomic
In-Reply-To: <199508120156.UAA14676@Shamino.quincy.edu>
Message-Id: <Pine.OSF.3.91j.950811193421.9041A-100000@becker1.u.washington.edu>
Mime-Version: 1.0
Content-Type: TEXT/PLAIN; charset=US-ASCII
Sender: owner-nomic-discussion@teleport.com
Precedence: bulk
Reply-To: nomic-discussion@teleport.com
Status: RO

On Fri, 11 Aug 1995, Don Blaheta wrote:

> >   - For each object of Type "rule" in the gamestate, in order
> >     of PrecedenceNumber, the value of the "if" attribute is
> >     evaluated.  If the result if "false", we proceed to the
> >     next "rule" object.  If the result is "true", the verbs in the
> >     "then" attribute fire, creating or deleting or modifying or
> >     scheduling objects; then we restart this "for" loop, back at
> >     the rule with the highest (lowest-numbered) PrecendenceNumber.

	I see some definite possibilities for abuse, by generating 
infinite loops.  If someone sneaks a rule in that evaluates to true right 
after another one does. . which evalutes to true after the first one 
does.  It will just keep restarting.
	You could either
	A)
		not restart the loop, and say that if a high-precedence 
rule evaluates to false once, it won't recheck for a particular move.  I 
don't really like this.
	B)
		have a very high precedence rule that checks to see how 
many times it's been checked. . if it's something phenomenal, it breaks 
the loop.
	C)  	
		Have a %reevalute flag on an object.  If that flag is on, 
then -- when the object is modified -- you trickle through the rules again.

	D>
		Just be careful :)

>   ObjectNumber: 7
>   PrecedenceNumber: 10
>   Type: rule
>   When: Type == move,
>         Subtype == register,
>         RegisterName NOT IN Name
>   Do: create ( Type: player,
>                Name: RegisterName,
>                Email: Sender )

	Hmmm.  I like the idea of a formalized rulesystem.  However, that 
doesn't mean that the player input has to be formalized.  You could have 
a player send a message to a designated coder with something like "i 
wanna be a player", and the coder could codify that for the system.  
Similarly, there could be people designated to interpret output for 
non-coder types.  If there is an ambiguity, or a field that the Player 
didn't specify, the coder can discuss it with them.


> 
>   ObjectNumber: 14
>   PrecedenceNumber: 15
>   Type: rule
>   When: $t = exists( Type == player,
>                      Score > 99 )
>   Do: Win = true,
>       Winner = $t


	Hmm. .but you may want side-effects to happen after a win.  Most
notably, you'd want to notify the Players.  With the above scheme, you'd
just have another ruleobject constantly check the win condition.  If it's
true, do happy things to the gamestate, reset the win condition to 0, and
tell everyone that $t won.  However, i prefer the idea of an separate
object. .the win object, that only acts when its called by another object. 
This object would do all of those happy things when necessary, without
constantly having to check them. 


	I'm hyperultrakeen on this system. . at least as an experiment.  
I wouldn't want to use it in lieu of Agora, as the semantic quibbling is 
half the fun of this game.  But it would be a great side-project.  And if 
it's done well, I think alot of other groups would be interested.  If you 
want some help working on the format/language/interface/hierarchy/theory 
or otherwise, write me.

				-SugarWater

