Well done, well done!!

I just have a few minor comments:


>101:
>Oerjan, 024:
>Players have to abide to the Rules even in out-of-game actions.

Relatively early in the game, I submitted a paradox CFJ based on
the fact that "obeying the Rules" conflicted with precedence Rules
which allowed one to not obey the Rule with lower precedence in a
conflict.  The Judge ruled (quite wisely, IMO) that "the Rules" in
Rule 101 referred to the Ruleset as a single entity, and not to
each individual Rule.  Thus, it is not in violation of Rule 101 to
disobey the Rule with lower precedence in a conflict.
(Sorry, I have no idea what the number on that CFJ would be.)


>991:
>Chuck, 035:
>The CFJ must be called on a statement, not on a subordinate clause (like
>"I request a Call for Judgement on whether...")

First, you have the CFJ number wrong here; I know it was more recent than 
that!  Second, I thought this was ruled the other way--that a "statement"
did not necessarily mean a statement in the grammatical sense, and
subordinate clauses could be CFJ'd on.  After much
persuasion, I was finally convinced of the error of my ways.

Chuck

