>        I see some definite possibilities for abuse, by generating
>infinite loops.  If someone sneaks a rule in that evaluates to true right
>after another one does. . which evalutes to true after the first one
>does.  It will just keep restarting.

Yep!  Anyone who can get the players to vote in a rule that
causes an infinite loop should probably will the game.  That
could be done most easily in the Mechanics, although that's
not a good place for it, since it can't be changed within
the game.  Best solution that springs to my mind is a very
early-precedence rule that counts (using a special counter
the changing of which doesn't reset rule-evaluation) how many
times it's been popped during this event-chain, and launches
a special object when it finds it's been lots and lots.
That special object would then have to cause a win, and all
the results of that Win, without falling back into the
infinite loop.  Which could be tricky!  Anyone causing an
infinite loop in comparatively early rules would probably
have to be awarded a win at the Mechanics level as a
fallback.

>>   ObjectNumber: 7
>>   PrecedenceNumber: 10
>>   Type: rule
>>   When: Type == move,
>>         Subtype == register,
>>         RegisterName NOT IN Name
>>   Do: create ( Type: player,
>>                Name: RegisterName,
>>                Email: Sender )

I must have missed the note in which Vanyel twiddles my
original syntax.  Could someone send it to me?

> I wouldn't want to use it in lieu of Agora, as the semantic quibbling is
> half the fun of this game.  But it would be a great side-project.

Absolutely!  This would be a very very different game from Agora;
Agora brought it to mind as much by contrast as by similarity...

