Has anyone considered a formal nomic along the lines of a Prolog-like language?
I.e., a series of productions. I am rather rusty on these languages, but it
might look something like this. Obviously, this is a mere example, and is far
from complete. To express even the mechanism for voting, proposing, and rule
set maintainence would require dozens, if not hundreds, of productions


passes(proposal(p)) := number_of_votes(p,for) > number_of_votes(p,against)
add_to_rule_set(r) := passes(proposal(p)) && is_new_rule_proposal(p,r)
remove_from_rule_set(r) := passes(proposal(p) && is_rule_repeal(p,r)
player_votes(player,proposal,choice) := 
    sends_message(player, i_vote(proposal,choice)


Just something to think about. I have no interest personally in expanding on
this idea. But it seems to me that a prolog-like syntax may be ideal for this.
The Rules would be the productions, and are manipulated by the same logic as
all the other entities. Everything would be completely formal, and the sole
inputs would be the sends_message(player,msg) primitive construct.


-- KoJen

