Chuck asks:
> Someone protoed some time ago to get rid of Assessor's choice on
> proposals where VI=AI, and just make such Proposals automatically
> fail.  What happened to that?

It failed.  I wasn't particularly fond of it--obviously, a Proposal
which ties is good enough to *almost* pass, and will almost certainly be
reproposed, thus wasting our time.

So it's a matter of who or what is the tiebreaker.  Currently, it is the
Assessor, which to me seems ok if not great.  I thought about making it
the Speaker, as a sort of reward, but the Speaker already has Champion's
Rights, so this would give em an effective four votes, which is
unacceptable.  In another vein I thought about making a pragmatic rule
which would make it illegal to tie a Proposal.  In other words, the last
person to send in a vote on that Proposal had made it tie, and so would
not be able to vote.  *That* poses some interesting tactical challenges,
but of course it gives the Assessor (who is already overburdened) way
too much work.  Another possibility is something called a Tie-o-tron (or
whatever), which people could submit Marks to, and a vote--it would work
like the Vototron did but wouldn't be considered unless there was a tie.
Another tactical challenge, but of course it is mostly a Mark sink, and
it would have to have a default vote anyway.  (FOR to emulate current
behaviour, AGAINST to emulate Chuck and Kelly's preference.)  It could
be given to the person with the most Kudos to choose, but this is so
often one of the recent Champions, it seems, that this is undesirable
for the same reasons as Speaker's Choice.  (It also has the disadvantage
of delaying the Voting Results.)  Likewise on the person with the most
Points, but of course that person will probably soon be Champion anyway.
YA alternative would be to, if the vote came out as a tie, make the
voting Sane and see if that ties as well (IOW, ignore Groups,
Aristocrats, and EVs--which would, of course, still be cast, just
ignored).  Alternatively, consider *only* EVs, as people who cast EVs
are usually the most concerned with the issue.  The only real problem
with that is that occasionally there is an FA or 2AF vote--they'd just
have to specify which was the EV.  (There isn't a problem with no EVs
having been cast, really--if a Proposal is so controversial as to tie,
someone knows it and will cast EVs.  Plus, this will catalyze people
casting more EVs.)

Well, that's *that* brainstorm, I'll let someone else sort through that
and comment.

> Chuck

Vanyel

