Kelly sez:
> "Adrian" == Adrian Brown <gorgonne@becker.u.washington.edu> writes:
> 
> Adrian> 	As long as people are toting around 800 Marks, there's
> Adrian> really no point in keeping the MUQ at .1.  Originally, I was
> Adrian> planning on shooting for a MUQ of 1, but that may be too
> Adrian> drastic.  The conservatives would have my head on a platter.
> 
> the average american makes something like $25,000 a year.  but we
> still have pennies.  i see no reason to change the MUQ.

Not for long--go to almost any store and they will tell you about the
penny shortage.  A few stores in the Chicago area are paying greater
than 1c for pennies, just because they're so unpopular and usually
find their way into pennyjars in people's houses.  In fact, I believe
the last time I used a penny was over four months ago.

Of course, this is entirely irrelevant to what the MUQ of Marks should
be.  Since Marks are now very much tied to Points, and the MUQ of
Points is 0.1, it seems silly for Marks to have an MUQ less than that.
Personally, I wouldn't oppose an MUQ of 1 for Marks, I think it would
make things, in general, to be easier.  (Of course, I'd say the same
thing about Points, too.)

