Vlad sez:
> * Have a "complete" Ruleset and a "proceduiral" Ruleset, which
> would contain only those Rules dealing with game mechanics
> (e.g. Proposals, Voting, the Courts). This would be analagous
> to the Nomic-Official/Nomic-discussion distinction. Allow players
> to chose which they receive in the weekly mailing (this is
> really my pet peeve).

Not a bad idea, but of course how do we decide which are which?

> * Let's work on shorter Rules. ElJefe points out there are now
> 207 Rules compared to 198 when he joined. But I bet the size of
> the Ruleset has doubled. This is a bad trend. We want people
> to understand the Rules.

Much agreed.

> * Preserve flexibility. The Contest system is extremely flexible,
> and I am sure we haven't exhausted its possibilities. Conflating
> it with the Group system is undesirable as long as we have group
> voting. Group voting requires restrictions on membership, minimum
> size, etc. (as well as creating political animosities) which
> are inimical to the Contest idea.

Picture this: a broad class of Corporate Entities, to which multiple
Players may belong, and which may require Players to do certain things.
Contracts, Contests, and Groups would each be special cases of these
Corporate Entities, but a whole lot of code could be consolidated.  (An
interesting thought: one particular instantiation of a Corporate Entity
could be the Jail....)

> * Try to accomplish goals without new Rules. Kojen is right that
> Contests are not strictly necessary. I do think the Rules serve the
> purposes of 1) encouraging their creation (by their very existence),
> 2) providing a readily comprehensible format, assisting their formation.
> Contracts, on the other hand, are rather superfluous. Ronald claims
> not all Players are honorable, but there are many ways of dealing
> with such people.

Contracts serve a definite purpose in the game, which I am not ready to
get rid of without replacing (see above)

> * Reduce the burden on Officers by distributing their duties among
> the Players as much as possible. E.g. allowing anyone to act as
> CotC by sending a CFJ to nomic-official. It's good for players to
> serve Agora, but most current Offices are too onerous. DIstributing
> responsibility will also make us think twice about adding
> bureaucratic complexity. We should use the judging system as a model
> (i.e. everybody gets to do it, it is salutary to the Players judging,
> and the individual burdens are not too hard).

Actually, Officer's duties are currently at a relative low.  The Banker
and Scorekeepor need only (perhaps "only" is a bad word, but...) record
transfers of Marks and Points, and any Player with a mind to could check
their work easily.  The Herald and Tabulator track WT, Kudo, and Blot
movement.  The Promotor merely distributes Proposals sent to em.  The
CotC distributes CFJs and Appeals sent to em.  The Rulekeepor takes 
new and amended rules and sticks them in eir Ruleset. The Assessor is
the most onerous duty, having to tally people's Votes *and* track EVs
*and* track the Potato *and* track Powers... but I really don't see any
easy way to split up eir job.  In any case, the Officers aren't as busy
as they used to be, for the most part.

> Vlad

Vanyel

