Favor protoes:

> ProtoProposal FAVO32, AI=1
> Political Parties
> 
> Create a Rule called "Political Parties Defined", with
> the following text:
> 
>   Let there be a class of Nomic Entities known as
>   "Political Parties".  Each Player may belong to
>   at most one Political Party.  A Player may, at
>   most once per Nomic Week, change eir Party affiliation
>   by so informing the Registrar.  New Players entering
>   the Game initially belong to a Party as specified
>   in other Rules.

Timing problems, again.  "A Player changes eir Party affiliation by
announcing that change to the Public Forum.  That change takes effect at
the beginning of the following Nomic Week."

>   If one or more transfers take place at the end of
>   the Voting Period for a Proposal, and said transfers
>   are the direct result of membership in some
>   Political Party, it shall be the responsibility of
>   the executor of the Treasury to which the transfer
>   is make to detect and report said transfers,
         ^ d
>   unless some other rule explicitly specifies a
>   different responsible Player.

Please tell me you aren't suggesting that _each Player_ spam the
Scorekeepor with requests after every Voting Period?

Here we have a large overlap of Officer duty.  On the one hand, Parties
are heavily involved with Point transfers, which are the domain of the
Scorekeepor; on the other, they are heavily involved with voting
tallies, which are the domain of the Assessor.  On the third hand (in
Agoraspace, who's to say what I look like?) it would make sense to have
the membership rolls kept by the Registrar.  No matter what there will
have to be communication going on, but what would minimize it?  The
Assessor's already the busiest job, so I'd say the Scorekeepor, even
though that initially seems a bit odd.

> Amend Rule 312 to read:
> 
>   Let there be a Political Party known as "the
>   Civic Duty Party".  At the end of the Voting
>   Period for a Proposal, each Player belonging
>   to the Civic Duty Party who voted on the Proposal
>   receives 1 Point from the Bank.  New Players entering
>   the Game initially belong to this Party.

"Civic Duty Party"... I like that.

>   The Assessor shall detect and report all transfers
>   resulting from this Rule, and shall do so no later
>   than the time e announces the Voting Results for
>   the relevant Proposals.

Either the Assessor should detect _all_ Party-based transfers, or none.
I vote the Scorekeepor should do it, as that would seem to minimize
communication.

> Create a Rule called "The Contrarian Party", with the
> following text:
> 
>   Let there be a Political Party known as "the
>   Contrarian Party".  At the end of the Voting
>   Period for a Proposal, each Player belonging to
>   the Contrarian Party who voted AGAINST that
>   Proposal receives 2 Points from the Bank, if
>   the Proposal passes.  At the end of the Voting
>   Period for a Proposal, each Player belonging
>   to the Contrarian Party who voted FOR that
>   Proposal receives 2 Points from the Bank, if
>   the Proposal fails.

I hate having the duplicated language, but I really can't see any way
around it.  Oh well.  You might at least shorten the sentences by
folding the "if" part of it into the rest of the sentence, i.e. "At the
end of the VP for a passing Proposal..."  (Makes it easier to read,
too.)

> Create a Rule called "The Majoritarian Party", with
> the following text:
> 
>   Let there be a Political Party known as "the
>   Majoritarian Party".  At the end of the Voting
>   Period for a Proposal, each Player belonging to
>   the Majoratarian Party who voted FOR that
>   Proposal, except the Proposor, receives 1 Point from
>   the Bank, if the Proposal passes.  At the end of the
>   Voting Period for a Proposal, each Player belonging
>   to the Contrarian Party who voted AGAINST that Proposal,
>   except the Proposor, receives 2 Points from the Bank,
>   if the Proposal fails.

Why exclude the Proposer?  Also, why only one point for FOR votes?
That's just asking for a failing proposal.  Finally, you should fold the
"if" clause into the rest of the sentence.

> Create a Rule called "The Progressive Party", with
> the following text:
> 
>   Let there be a Political Party known as "the
>   Progressive Party".  At the end of the Voting
>   Period for a Proposal, each Player belonging to
>   the Progressive Party receives 1 Point from the
>   Bank, if the Proposal passes, and contains one
>   or more Rule Changes that create a new Rule.

Ok.  As I see it, the way parties should work is, if a member of any
party voted unintelligently, e would average 1 point per proposal.  That
makes the whole party thing a skill game, in which party to join and
which proposals to vote for and against.  But nobody will join the
progressive or minimalist parties, if their relatively uncommon payoffs
will make them automatically win less than 1 point.

> Create a Rule called "The Minimalist Party", with
> the following text:
> 
>   Let there be a Political Party known as "the
>   Minimalist Party".  At the end of the Voting
>   Period for a Proposal, each Player belonging to
>   the Minimalist Party receives 2 Points from the
>   Bank, if the Proposal passes, and contains one
>   or more Rule Changes that repeal an existing Rule.

See above, although at least the payoff here is better (I'd recommend 2
for Progressive and 3 for Minimalist, though.)

>       - Various people suggested collasping the pairs
>         of sentences in Contrarian and Majoritarian into
>         one each, but I think that makes the meaning much
>         less clearly-expressed.

I agree.  I'd love to see them collapsed, but I really don't see how.

>       - There were also suggestions that Progressives and
>         Minimalists should only get their rewards if they
>         voted FOR the Proposal in question, but I tend to
>         think it's more fun the other way (there might be
>         some sneaky reason to have to vote AGAINST it, but
>         one could still lobby FOR it in hope of a Party point).

I like them this way.

>       - Open Question: is the Registrar the right person to
>         keep track of these things?

See above.

>       - Open Question: should Party affiliations be listed in
>         some periodic official report?

Yes.  (This could just be a single letter after their names in the
Scorekeepor's report, or something.  On that note, you might want to
make each party start with a different letter... Civic Duty can be
abbreviated to D, but there's still a namespace collision between
Majoritarian and Minimalist.  Perhaps "Sheep" for the former, or
"Reduction" for the latter?)

>       - Open Question: the point values here are quite small;
>         should they be multipied by (say) two or five or
>         ten to make Parties more important?

At most by two, but probably not even that much... a clever player could
make as much as 12-16 Points per week just for voting, which is more
than salaries... the only other source of Points is Proposing, which I
think should be more valuable than voting.

Vanyel

