favor writes:
>> such a world would be boring; there would be no challenge, no
>> motivation.
>
>Yeah, so says also one side of my mind.  Of course, if we
>got rid of the scarcity that the current RL economies are
>based on, there'd turn out to be new scarce things that
>economies would grow up around.

Ah, Economy, my fourth favourite subject!
I agree with Favor that we shouldn't introduce scarcity
just to have an economy. Economy is not so much
about scarcity, but more about exchanges of things
that are scarce in one place, but no in another.

So far an economy, by which I think of an frequent
exchange of objects, did not spontaneously develop.
That is, because we value too much the only scarce
objects that we have, i.e. votes.

Votes are rarely sold by Players. It seems that everybody
is happy with having eir One Vote, to influence the game.
It seems to be more important, apparently, that a Player
has *some* weight in the decision proces, rather than that
e bothers to try to increase this weight. (There are exceptions
to the rule of course.)

The point in case is Michael's MVs, who are never ever used.

For this reason an economy around votes could not develop.

Introducing the EVs, didn't really help. Some Players are using
them to double or triple their voting weight, but they are
hardly ever traded. (Although did you notice that 15 EVs changed
hands this yesterday? I wonder what that was about :-)

The conclusion is, obviously, that we yet have to find a scarce
object that will do the trick. Votes don't work: they are not
scarce enough, for people to try to get them by commercial ways.

>to my liking for Complexity in general: some side of me
>says that if we just made Agora full enough of complex and
>neat and interesting mechanisms, there would of necessity
>turn out to be scarce things that economies would naturally
>evolve around (without our having to intentionally hack
>them together).

Maybe, maybe, but so far we never came up with such an valuable
and scarce item.
And the proposals to scarcify (is that a word?) items, that are
now plentiful (like votes), receive a lukewarm reception.
This is not different from what happens with Social Security or
Smoking or Television: once people are hooked, it's hard to
kick the habit.

Nevertheless, the Agora Welfare State -in which Officers
and Judges are paid for by an infinite Treasury, and where
the hard work going into Proposal writing (and thusly,
providing entertainment for the other Players) is rewarded
by the same meaningless Points-  might benefit from some
confrontation with TANSTAAFL!

Imagine that Officers, Judges and Successfull Proposal
Writers were rewarded by Votes. Imagine that you have to
earn the right to Vote.

What would happen?
First of all, Offices would become more valuable and Players
more critical of Officer errors and misbehaviour. When was
the last time that an Officer was kicked out of Office by
a Proposal?
Secondly, Judges have to be more careful: after all, if there
Judgment is overruled that would lose the Votes earned.
Thirdly, Proposal voting behaviour would become different:
not only would a vote lose the Voter a Vote, that could have been
spend elsewhere; but a Proposal would only be accepted, if a Player
feels that e benefits from the particular Rule Change.

Quite a different Agora Universe, isn't it?

>Still, I'd like to re-make the underlying point: is it
>really unthinkable that there might be interesting things
>that the Agoran Pubic would be willing to do that *aren't*
>about as colorful and emotionally involving as (say) hog-belly
>futures?

That question is of course related to the reason why we play
Nomic rather than hog-belly futures or chess. I like discussion,
the confrontation of ideas and opinions: I drink the Swann-Kelly
exchanges as wodka and the mailsalvos after a Scam taste like
caviar to me.
`Interesting things' that increase my appetite are therefore
welcome.

>P.S. Responses about how emotional some people do in fact
>     get about hog-belly futures are assumed, and need not
>     actually be sent...

I wouldn't know: what *are* hog-bellies?

TAL

