the only problem i can really see with privatizing the scorekeepor
(which is to say, not having any "official" scores) is that it makes
it much more likely for a claim of a win by points to be contested by
a CFJ, and further that judging such a CFJ will be difficult.

why?  as Scorekeepor i have to post score reports at least once a
week.  people have ample opportunity to examine these for errors and
tell me that i fucked up so i can fix it.

without public review of scorekeeping efforts, errors could propogate
and persist for weeks, even months (i anticipate game length
increasing considerably, barring lots of win by tokens).  the chances
are that when a player finally does win, the claim will be contested
(because one of the half-dozen amateur scorekeepors will have a
different total score for that player, one for which the claimant does
not win).  the judge is going to have to sift through potentially
thousands of posts to reconstruct the true scores, and few judges will
have the ability or the desire to do so, and will end up judging
UNKNOWN, leaving us just as confused as before.

other points.  suppose i'm keeping score privately and notice that
some Player has won.  however, being a crafty fellow, i don't mention
this to anyone.  that Player himself either isn't keeping score
himself or has an error in his score tallies that have him not winning
for some reason.  so he doesn't report it either (believing that he
hasn't actually won yet).  eventually, it is found out, say, a month
later, that he actually one a month before.  what is to be done?  this
is somehting of a problem with the current system, but it's not as
severe, because the Scorekeepor is _required_ to announce a Win by
Points within seven days of it happening.

k.
--
