Morendil writes:

>Or, even, of the very old question about science : are scientific
>discoveries really 'discoveries', or do we somehow "create" the
>universe when we describe it ?

The latter, sort of.
In fact the Great Architect created the world as described in Genesis 1.
But just when He finished writing up His creation in chapter 1 of
His Thesis (the Experimental Set-up) disaster struck.

Human beings became curious and started to investigate
nature. First the GA was pleased with this. But in Middle Ages or so
people on Earth became convinced that the Earth was spherical. The idea
amused the GA and He changed the Flat Earth into a sphere. Just in time,
as it turned out, otherwise Columbus would have fallen of.

But then this guy Copernicus concluded that the earth turned around the
Sun and not the other way around, which forced another change upon the
GA. Next Darwin wanted evolution, which forced Him to deposit fossils
everywhere; then geologist and astronomers wanted the earth to be
4.5x10^9 years old and not the miserable 6600 the GA had needed.

Big Bang, several dozens of elementary particles, floating continents
and General Relativity later the Creation looked quite different from
the original Blueprints.

Then came Schrodinger, his cat and, gulp, Quantum Mechanics.
Here the GA was flabbergasted.

First of all, He didn't understand the theory. After all, He had
an Architects diploma, not one in Theoretical Physics.
Secondly, He started to have enough of these humans who were never
-never!- satisfied with nature as He had created it.

So, He decided to make it all random.
Some physicist let photons fly, to see where they went?
Fine, sometimes they would go here, sometimes there.
Another one, counted nuclear decays. OK, but chances were that
the next one would not come before next week.
Particles were being collided in huge accellerators. No problem,
let them count the pieces, if they wanted.

This new stratagem let the GA have peace, at last, and time to finish
writing up his Thesis. Or so He thought....

Of course, as we all now, Suber came and invented Nomic.

TAL

