Kelly sez:
> "Steven" == Steven A Swiniarski <gb485@cleveland.Freenet.Edu> writes:
> 
> Steven> A Rule says they're now Organizations....  
> 
> no, they don't.  i can't find a single thing in the Rules that speaks
> to the state of Groups created prior to the passage of Proposal 1760.

Ok.  Here is the text of the Groups rule, commented by me:

>      Let there be a Class of Organization known as a Group.

Well.  It has already been hashed out that this was badly phrased, but I
have a number of ideas on the matter.

1) How would you react if the sentence read "Let there be a type of
Organization known as a Group"?  To me, at least, it clears up the
ambiguity in a way that is consistent with prior play--which seems as
good a criterion as any.

2) Try reading it grouped a bit differently: "Let there be a Class of
(Organization known as a Group)".   It helps, a bit, I think...

3) It seems possible if not obvious that the name "Group" refers to
instantiations of this Class of Organization, or at least that it may
refer to both the Class and the instantiations.  Why is this so
difficult to see?

>     A Group's Compact consists only of Statutes, and are known
>     collectively as its Ordinances, an individual Statute of its
>     Compact is known as an Ordinance.  Its Administrator is known as
>     the Group's Ordinancekeepor.  A Group has one Treasury, and its
>     Executor is known as the Group's Vizier.

Perhaps that second comma should be a semicolon, but otherwise this
paragraph seems to unambiguously state the fate of prior Groups--we know
what their Ordinances were, and it says here that the Statutes of Groups
are known as its Ordinances.  Well, that's cleared up.  We know what a
Treasury is, and we know what a Vizier is--now we know that the Vizier
is the Group's Executor.

>     A Group has an associated form of Currency.  The generic name of
>     all Group Currencies is "Coins."  The specific name of a Group's
>     Currency is <name> Coins, where <name> is the Name of the Group.

This is unchanged, I think.

>     Players within the Ordinances' Jurisdiction are known as the
>     Group's Membership.  Both the Vizier and the Ordinancekeepor of
>     the Group must be Members of the Group.  At all times there must
>     be a Vizier and Ordinancekeepor for every Group.

We know what a Membership is; now we know that it is aka a Jurisdiction.


According to Kelly, an Amend is exactly equivalent to a Repeal-Enact
cycle.  I disagree.  An Amendment modifies a rule, while a Repeal-Enact
replaces it.  More importantly, according to Game Custom, with a
Repeal-Enact there is an infinitesimal time where *the rule does not
exist*.  Providing a discontinuity.  But with Amendment, there is no
such discontinuity.


To provide insight into my point of view, reflect on each of the
following scenarios, and the change in state prior to and following each
example (specifically, what happens to pre-existing and pre-owned entities
of the type being discussed):

1) Players can own various numbers of Puppetheads; the rule defining how
Puppetheads are created is amended to fix a typo.

2) Players can own various numbers of Footsteps; the rule defining how
Footsteps are created is modified so that they are only created once a
week, instead of twice a week as before.

3) Players can own various numbers of Klaws; the rule defining how
Klaws are created is modified so that two people must apply for a
Klaw, instead of one person paying for it.

4) Players can own various numbers of Toupees, which may be Red or
Black; the rule defining Toupees is modified so that there may be Red,
Black, or Purple Toupees.

5) Players can own various numbers of Constantinoples, which can hold
Marks and Points, and each have titles; the rule defining
Constantinoples is modified to rename Constantinoples to Istanbuls
(though other properties remain the same).

6) Players can own various numbers of Spiders, which have many
properties spread out through five different rules; in a consolidation
move those five rules are repealed and in the same proposal, a new rule
is enacted with all the information from the five rules.

7) Players can own various numbers of Fingertips, which have many properties
spread out through five different rules; in a consolidation move the
first of those rules is amended to include all the information from
itself and the other four, and the other four are repealed.

8) Players can own various numbers of Spies, which have many
properties listed in one massive rule; in a diversification move that
rule is repealed and five smaller rules are created which contain all
the info from the big one.

9) Players can own various numbers of Thermostats, which have many
properties listed in one massive rule; in a diversification move that
rule is amended to include only a small portion of that info, and four
new rules are enacted which contain the rest of the info.

I'm playing with a number of variables here, and I'd like you to
seriously consider what happens to the entities held by the players
before proposals 1-9 occurred.

Thought about it?  Here are my "answers" (your mileage may vary):

1) This is the simplest case--according to Game Custom dating back
forever, and almost requisite to a playable game of Nomic, this type of
amendment should not change prior holdings.  People who held Puppetheads
before #1 hold just as many after #1.

2) Game Custom would seem to imply that such "minor" changes as
this--merely a modification in frequency of creation of Footsteps.
Presumably, Footstep holdings would not change as a result of #2--no
need to grandfather the old ones.

3) This is a more "major" change, of course--after #3 passed, there
would probably be people who got Klaws before who couldn't get them
after (at least not as easily).  But, I think, they still hold what
Klaws they have.

4) As a result of #4, a new "type" of Toupee is allowed.  Does this mean
that prior Red & Black Toupee holdings are invalidated?  I doubt it,
although I suppose some people would think so.  IMO, though, people
would keep their old Toupees.

5) The _only_ thing being changed here is the name of the entity
itself--however, I (and I'd guess most others, too) believe that there
would have to be a self-repealing rule to convert Constantinoples to
Istanbuls.  Even though these two things are functionally identical, and
there are even less functional changes than in 2-4 which didn't require
a grandfathering, the name-change is important enough in a continuity
determination that I think a bootstrapping is required.

6) I would say, "well *sure* Spider holdings would remain the same".
Even though the original rule does not exist, at all, in any form--there
are only completely new rules in its place.  I expect there will be much
disagreement on this one, and I am hazy enough on it that I might back
down that position.

7) Just because one rule is only amended, does that change things?  Does
it matter _which_ of the five rules is amended?  I dunno.  I *think*
Fingertip holdings stay the same.

8) Again, none of the original rules exist--does that force a
discontinuity?  Does the _order_ of the RCs in the proposal matter?
There's a debatable question.  I'm inclined to say that Spy holdings
remain, but again that is a tough question. _Why_ do they stay the same?

9) Does merely amending the original rule matter?  I'm inclined to say
it might, but like I said, it's very debatable.  Probably,
Thermostat-holders keep their Thermostats without a grandfather cluase,
and it's somewhat more definite than #8, but still a tad problematic.


SO you see, there are a _lot_ of questions to be resolved over the
continuity of Entity existence.  If I weren't so busy, I'd go for my
M.N. over it, but if anyone else wants to flesh out the topic, feel
free.

> k.

Vanyel

