Kelly sez:
> "Steven" == Steven A Swiniarski <gb485@cleveland.Freenet.Edu> writes:
> 
> Steven> This is only because some Players deny the identity
> Steven> Groups=Groups.  I fail to see the logic of insisting
> Steven> otherwise.
> 
> the identity that is being denied is "thing named Groups = another
> thing names Groups". it's quite clear that Groups pre-1760 and Groups
> post-1760 are different from one another, if only because pre-1760
> they weren't Organizations and post-1760 they are.

Is name important?  I think it is.

> Steven> Why does changing the rule:
> 
> Steven> "<X> is <Y>, <Z> and <Q>" to "<X> is <Y>, <Z> and part of <L>"
> 
> Steven> Neceitate that for some bizzare instant of time all <X> cease
> Steven> to exist?
> 
> 766/2 defined a Group as an entity possessing certain properties.
> 766/3 defines a Group as "a Class of Organizations".  now, a class is
> a collection of similar things.  i can't, for the life of me, see how
> a collection of things is in any way identical with a single entity
> endowed with certain properties.

Not exactly.  766/2 defined "Groups", and named some properties held by
each Group.  766/3 defines a Class of Organizations, whose instances are
called "Groups", and names some properties held by each such instance.

> even if we choose to ignore 766's equivocation over the term "Group"
> (it uses it both as the designation for the class Entity and also as a
> generic term for each instance of that class),

I see no problem with this--you program in Perl, Kelly, you should be
able to understand the idea of separate namespaces.

>                                                the problem remains
> that there is no authority within the Rules that makes the entities
> formerly defined by the Rules to be Groups the same as these new
> Groups.  simply put, naming does not imply identity.

Ahem.  See my prior post--naming may not be everything, but it's
important.

> Steven> I maintain that, in fact, the sudden destruction of all Groups
> Steven> is one *hell* of an arbitrary change of Game entities.
> 
> it's supported by Game Custom: when an Entity previously created under
> the authority of the Rules is no longer authorized to exist under
> those same Rules, it ceases to exist.  if you like, you can choose to
> believe that X Group, etc. continue to exist, but as their existence
> has no significance as far as the Rules are concerned (because the
> Rules which once granted them meaning under the Rules no longer do so)
> they might as well not exist.

So, just because the rules governing _creation_ of an Entity cease to
exist, that Entity ceases to exist?  I postulate the following snippet
of rules:

2101: There exist entities called Accordions.
2102: Accordions are created weekly and given to each Player.
2103: A Player's Accordions are destroyed when a Player deregisters.

Now, if 2102 is repealed, do the previously-held Accordions still exist?
If 2101 is repealed?  If both 2101 and 2102 are repealed but not 2103?
If 2101 never existed, and 2102 were repealed, would the Accordions
still exist?  How much about an Entity must be specified in the Rules
for it to exist?

> the problem with claiming that the old Groups somehow became
> Organizations as a consequence of the adoption of 1760 is that there
> is no basis in the Rules at all for this to have taken place.  Groups
> were Entities created under the Rules, and causing them to become
> Organizations without a specific Rule permitting that is a change to
> an Entity created by the Rules by an action other than those specified
> by the Rules, and is therefore clearly forbidden by Rule 1011.

Individual Groups were Entities under the old Rules.  The individual
Groups have not changed--only the rules which govern them.  (I.e. now
the rules for Organizations as well as the rules for Groups apply.)

> k.

Vanyel

