Steve sez:
> 4 might be workable, but would certainly be at the low end. I've played
> it once or twice in ftf mode. It worked ok, although there wasn't time
> for very many Rule Changes. It's very different to playing via email.

I might point out that it would be entirely possible to organize a Nomic
Society, which met once a week or so, and the rules continue all week.
That is, you are playing Nomic 24-7 for the duration of this thing.  Of
course, this could be as silly or as serious as you want; if you wanted,
you could enact a rule like "if you see another Nomician in the hallway,
you must jump straight up twice, and thump your fist on your chest", but
if you didn't want to, you could just have rules apply during the actual
meetings.

> I remember we passed a Rule that the first Player to say a word
> containing the letter 'x' after the Rule was adopted had to go
> outside and kiss the exhaust pipe of my freind Dexter's car, while the
> other players danced around the car in a circle singing "Hava Nagila".

Ah, what a fun game Nomic can be.  Reminds me of a few rules we had in
the Quasi-Mao game we played in high school.  (See, Mao has so many
rules, and has undergone so many world splits, that a couple of people
at my high school decided to start a new one, called Quasi-Mao,
essentially from scratch.  That was over four years ago, but last I
heard it was going strong, having undergone about thirty world splits
and with each ranging from fifty or sixty to a couple hundred rules...)

