"Don" == Don Blaheta <blahedo@quincy.edu> writes:

Don> This morning, I got email from one Dariush Gholizadeh, wondering if
Don> Agora Nomic would be interested in a business partnership.  I clarified
Don> the nature of Agora (an informal but international association of
Don> people) for him, and he responded with a more clear description of what
Don> he was working on.  Here, then, is his response and my response to it.
Don> (He requested that this be forwarded to you-all.)  In response to my
Don> question about the staff, he stated that young actors will be paid by
Don> his company for the recordings.

first of all, i think this idea is somewhat half-baked.  there just
isn't enough interest in Nomic to make such a venture profitable.

secondly, it infringes on Suber's IP rights.  Nomic is Suber's baby,
and anyone who tries to use Suber's Rules to make money is arguably
infringing on his copyright.  someone should get this brought to
Suber's attention (i don't offhand recall his email address).  i doubt
Suber intended for Nomic to be used for for-profit activities, and it
goes beyond the usual permissions to use his ideas for profit without
explicit permission.  

thirdly, it may infringe on our own IP rights.  if Mr. Gholizadeh will
provide a mailing address i'll be glad to put him on legal notice that
he is not permitted to use any of my creative output connected with
Agora for any purpose other than educational or entertainment, and
that such activity must, in any case, be with no intent to make a
profit.  i would suggest that

also note that i do not surrender my IP rights to my efforts here
merely because i am no longer a Player, and that entering into such a
partnership without attempting, at least, to contact every Player,
past and present, who has contributed substantially to the Game (e.g.,
Wes), would be of dubious ethicality at best, and would in theory put
all of us at legal liability.

legal stuff aside, someone should point him at Shattered World, which,
as i recall, ran a Nomic-like "government" within the game, that
Players could elect to become a part of.  Geoff Wong or Mike
McGaughey(sp) would have more information than i would, of ocurse.
Steve may be able to help here, since he knows Geoff and Mike a lot
better than i do. :)

i find the idea of a commericial Nomic unappealing for some reason.
i've thought that it might be nice to incorporate the Friends of Agora
Nomic as a non-profit organization which might then raise funds for
various purposes, but the idea of running a Nomic to make money--for
anyone other than the Players--galls me somewhat.  it's also contrary
to the Spirit of the Game, because the Rules pertaining to payment
would not be subject to being changed by the Players.

i have no interest in fancy real-time conferencing or other glitzy
"cyberspace" junk.  they won't contribute in any useful way to the
Game as i play it.

k.
--
kelly martin                                 <kelly@poverty.bloomington.in.us>

The American Hyphen Society is a community-based, not-for-profit, grass-roots,
conciousness-raising/education-research alliance that seeks to help effect the
across-the-board self-empowerment of wide-ranging culture-, nationality-,
ethnicity-, creed-, gender-, and sexual-orientation-defined identity groups by
excising all multiculturally-less-than-sensitive terminology from the English
language, replacing it with counter-hegemonic, cruelty-, gender-, bias-, and,
if necessary, content-free speech.  The society's motto is "It became
necessary to destroy the language to save it."  Its headquarters are in
Wilkes-Barre, Pennsylvania.  -- unknown

