kelly:

> secondly, it infringes on Suber's IP rights.  Nomic is Suber's baby,
> and anyone who tries to use Suber's Rules to make money is arguably
> infringing on his copyright.  someone should get this brought to
> Suber's attention (i don't offhand recall his email address).

I'm not sure it does, really; it certainly does in spirit, but I
suspect not in law?  This person could certainly start his own
for-profit Nomic-*like* game, since you can't copyright an idea,
unless Suber's *patented* the idea, which I really doubt.  He
could even call it "Nomic", since you can't copyright a title,
unless Suber's got it as a trademark, which I also really doubt.

He *probably* can't use any significant amount of text from
Agora Nomic itself.  I say "probably" because a case might be
made that by distributing the text in a world-accessible place
sans proprietary notices of any kind, we have effectively
given up some rights; I wouldn't expect such a case to win,
but IP law has surprised me many times in the past!

So while he'd perhaps take some karmic damage from starting
up a for-fee Nomic without Suber's permission, I doubt he'd
be violating any laws, as long as he doesn't (say) include
softcopy of Suber's book...

IMHO, if there are people who are willing to pay money
to this guy to take part in a Nomicy game that he's hosting,
more power to him.  If he does it badly, or no better than
equivalent free games that are available, he'll fail for
lack of customers, anyway.  My initial impression from his
note is that he is several miles from his first clue; on
the other hand, perhaps I'm just not sufficiently
forwardlooking!

| favor |

