On Fri, 10 Nov 1995, Charles E. Carroll wrote:

> I send a text, "Nile Spice Black Bean soup, prepared in Vladivostok
> by a Basque-speaking cook, shall be the official food of Agora," to
> the Promotor, labeled as a Proposal.  Thus, by 1483, it is a Proposal.

	Actually, it's neither a Rule Change nor a valid Directive.  So 
it's not.. . anyway. .


> 
> The Promotor distributes that via the PF, and as a result, the Promotor
> receives it.  Rule 1483 now says, (it being a text labeled as a Proposal
> and sent to the Promotor), that it is a Proposal.
> 
> Oooh!  Big suprise there!  My Proposal is a Proposal!!
> 
> The error that people seem to be making is in thinking that
> it is now a new, different Proposal.  There is nothing in 1483
> which suggests that.

	You're missing the point.  According to Rule 1036 (I think it's 
1036.  The Rule that defines the office of Promotor) Any Proposal 
received by the Promotor must numbered and submitted to the PF.  Once e 
does so, a literalist could interpret this such that e's received the 
Proposal again, and must number it again and resubmit it, ad infinitum.  
I tend to think Game Custom denies this.  Therefore, Game Custom allows 
for Proposals being sent to the PF, while not being submitted.

				-SaltWater

