Status: RO

Vanyel protos :
---
      The Rules in the Initial Set are in effect at the beginning of the
      first game.  The Initial Set consists of Rules 101-116 (Immutable)
      and 201-219 (Mutable).
---

Why should we keep this ?

---
      If for any reason any Player violates a Rule, penalties may be
      assessed as stipulated in other Rules, and the violation shall be
      retracted if possible.
---

This is far less innocuous than you seem to think. It is the very 
first notion I have seen (apart the Injuction on Retracting) that we 
should define when actions are applied to the Ruleset, and when 
they're not.

Apparently, Game Custom has been to do as we goddamn well
please. If it's too much trouble to undo a specific Move (because 
it's been CFJed illegal), then we keep it and sweep the embarrassing 
bits under the carpet. On the other hand, when a strategic Move is 
considered (not even Judged) illegal, a Player with enough political 
power may simply block that Move.

See the Mousetrap for a good example. The Move of its creation was 
immediately subject to doubt, but as the Judicial juggernaut trundled 
on, there was never a real intention to retract it, or keep the Game 
State frozen or whatever. The consensus seemed to be that even if 
MT's creation was illegal, it would *dissolve* upon finding that out, 
not be retroactively un-created.

On the other hand, Swann's election to Notary never really stood a 
chance. It was a totally legal Move, its legality was never contested 
through a CFJ, but Kelly effectively voided that Move by simply 
announcing that she refused to accept it.

Obviously, we can't have that sort of thing. That's despotism. If we 
want to recognize that kind of political power, we want it granted by 
the Rules.

Your new 101 has the effect of all Moves having effect immediately 
and being retracted only if Judged illegal. I submit that we need 
something more flexible, and I will Proto to that effect shortly.

