"Laurent" == Laurent Bossavit <morendil@micronet.fr> writes:

Laurent> A brief note on language : I learnt English exclusively by
Laurent> reading it.

arguably one of the best ways to learn any language.

Laurent> So, as a consequence, I have absolutely no formal knowledge
Laurent> of the English grammar,

that's ok, neither do most native English speakers.  English's formal
grammar, as taught in schools, is neither complete nor accurate.
grammarians are often noted for pedanticism, and many of them do not
"practice what they preach".  the most noted change of recent years
seems to be the acceptance of split infinitives; in the last several
years it has become more and more acceptable to split an infinitive.
the other example off the top of my head of a generally acceptable
agrammatical usage is the placement of a preposition at the end of a
sentence, which is strictly incorrect but incredibly common, and
probably owes to English's Germanic heritage (specifically, the large
number of Germanic verbs with separable prefixes).

k.
