the United States, at least, experienced a large influx of
Germanic-speaking people during the period between 1850 and 1900, many
of whome settled in the midwest.  their children will have had their
speech patterns colored by their parent's Germanic speech (my
grandmother is a classic example of this).  i suspect that this vector
reintroduced a number of Germanic influences into American English,
especially into the Midwest and Plains States.

i point out that many Minnesotan dialects still show a significant
Nordic influence in intonation and speech patterns, yet it has been
quite a while since a major wave of Nordic immigrants settled there.  

