Message-Id: <9511110626.4375@poverty.bloomington.in.us>
In-reply-to: "Laurent Bossavit"'s message of Sat, 11 Nov 1995 01:17:47 +0001 <199511110024.BAA04465@logatome.micronet.fr>
From: kelly@poverty.bloomington.in.us (Kelly Martin)
To: nomic-discussion@teleport.com
Subject: a rought theory of Moves (was: Re: BUS: PROTO : Classes of Moves)
Sender: owner-nomic-discussion@teleport.com
Precedence: bulk
Reply-To: nomic-discussion@teleport.com
Status: RO

needless to say, i don't believe Morendil's categorization of "Moves"
is adequate, and i have distinct problems with eir proposal.

first, it is well-established game custom to, in most cases, allow
Players to make conditional and/or deferred Moves, that may or may not
take place at some time in the (possibly) indefinite future.
Morendil's proposal would take away this ability, by requiring all
Moves to take place in the message describing them.  further
legislation could correct this shortcoming, but i believe it should be
brought forth.

secondly, Moves are not the result of email messages.  Moves _are_
Player Actions.  _Events_, which Morendil fails to define (the major
flaw in his conceptualization), are the results of Moves.  an Event is
any change in a Game Entity, including the creation of or destruction
of Game Entities, as well as changes to any property of existing
Entities (such as possession, location, or anything else that the
Rules might define).  the special case of Players is complicated; i
will deal with that shortly.

in any case, the sending of email, strictly speaking, is not an Game
Event, although some email messages (especially when sent to the
Public Forum) cause Events to take place.  since some Events take
place without any direct causation by a person (for example, the
payment of Officer's Salaries, which takes place automatically,
without any person specifically acting to cause these Events to take
place), there is a distinction between Moves and Events.  

a Move is any action taken by a _person_ (not necessarily a Player,
for a very important reason that will become apparent shortly) which
causes one or more Events (which may occur before, at the same time
as, or after the Move).  i find it easiest to construct the model such
that Moves themselves have no direct effect upon the Game State, but
may cause one or more Events to take place, which then affect the Game
State in some way.  therefore, sending email may (or may not) be a
Move, but it is never an Event: no Game Entity has the ability to send
email.

Moves themselves are not retractable (allowing retractability requires
creating another class of action called a Move Retraction, which
cannot be a Move itself, or a paradox arises), but it may be possible
that other Moves have the effect of nullifying another Move's ability
to cause some Event, and thus the Events resulting from a Move might
be caused to not occur, giving the appearance of retractability.
likewise, no Move is forbidden (in the logical sense) by the Rules;
the Rules have no power to forbid (that is, prevent) persons from
acting in any given way.  the Rules, however, do strictly control the
number, nature, and timing of the Events which occur as a result of a
given Move.

Players, because of their dual nature, both as Game Entnties and as
beings with existence independent of the Game, are confusing.  i have
found that it is best (in terms of the construction of a coherent
theory of Moves) to consider a Player to be a Game Entity "magically"
associated with one (or possibly more than one) person.  this
association is part of what allows a given ecto-Game action to cause
endo-Game Events.  there's at least one case where ecto-Game actions
by persons not associated with any Player can cause an Event, and that
is when a person who is not already a Player registers to become one.
this Move causes a number of Events to take place, the most
significant of which is the creation of the association between the
person and a Player that gives that person the broadened scope of
power to cause Events that characterizes Players.  note that all
persons have some limited power to cause Events; persons who happen to
be Players merely have (significantly) more power to do so.  again,
the Rules have complete control over the ability of Moves to cause
Events.

returning to Morendil's theory of Moves, we can see that it is
incomplete.  the Move of retracting another Move is clearly none of
the classes specified, because a retraction must "reach back" through
time and undo the Events caused by the Move now being denied legal
force; yet, Morendil defines Moves to be Events, and limits their time
to be the time of the email message that caused them, which seems
inconsistent with the inherently retroactive nature of a retraction.
perhaps it can be argued that this rule would be specifying an earlier
time for when the Move of retracting a Move would take place; however,
i am uncomfortable with this characterization of Moves in any case.

also, the Move of taking back a Move is temporally paradoxical: if a
Move is retroactively taken back at some point in the future, so that
it never took place, then how can the Move that caused it to have been
taken back itself take place, referring as it does to a Move that
never took place?  this is why i insist that Moves are inherently
nonretractable.  i believe that allowing Moves to cause Events to take
place temporally prior to when the Move is made (or to deny such
Events from taking place) is not necessarily paradoxical, although
this may lead to the situation where it cannot be determined with
finality whether or not a given Event has taken place.

a consequence of this principle is that "illegal" Moves are possible,
and in fact unregulated.  however, illegal Events are neither possible
nor permissible, and any Move which purports to have caused an illegal
Event simply did not do so.  the making of an Move, regardless of its
legality, cannot cause unpermitted Events to take place.  rather, the
making of an illegal Move by a person who is also a Player causes a
Rule Violation Event for that Player, with whatever consequent Events
occuring that the Rules may define.

the process of Judgement, then, consists of determining what Events
have or have not taken place, and when.  of course, calling for, and
making, Judgement is itself a Move, with consequent (or antecedent)
Events arising thereunto, so the levels become entangled when formal
Judgement is concerned.

sorry for the disjointedness of this essay.  i've been writing it over
the last couple of hours, while also fooling around with a badly
thrashing Linux machine.  my kingdom for another 8 megabytes!

k.
--
kelly martin                                 <kelly@poverty.bloomington.in.us>

		  "Lesbians in the sport hurt women's golf."
			-- CBS commentator Ben Wright

