On Fri, 10 Nov 1995, Kelly Martin wrote:

> the other example off the top of my head of a generally acceptable
> agrammatical usage is the placement of a preposition at the end of a
> sentence, which is strictly incorrect but incredibly common, and
> probably owes to English's Germanic heritage (specifically, the large
> number of Germanic verbs with separable prefixes).

It is really not about separable prefixes, there are two distinct issues.
You are referring to

"This is the table, on which I put the book"
(Actually "where" is the usual word here, but I can't think of a better
example at the moment.)

vs.

"This is the table that I put the book on"

I think German, like "formal" English, uses the former, and the latter is 
simply not compatible with modern German syntax. Both languages have 
their syntax heavily influenced by Latin, however (which also uses the 
former.)

In Norwegian it is the former form that is impossible. (Or rather, 
extremely archaic.)

Norwegian does not have separable prefixes - they are always separated, 
like English "look out", "show up", and are used in much the same way as 
in English.

> kelly martin                                 <kelly@poverty.bloomington.in.us>

Greetings,
Oerjan.

