Orjan sez:
> > Hmm, isn't that unlikely? German influences on English are much smaller
> > *now* than they were a century ago.
> 
> As an alternative interpretation, let me offer that both of the above
> "errors" were actually the original usage (inherited from the Germanic
> roots of English), and were never actually abandoned except by "educated"
> people; that the alternative "correct" usages were artificially implanted
> by Latin-inspired Grammarians, don't fit well into the English language,
> and are now being expelled in favor of the older usage. 

Well, English is hard to classify because it doesn't have a single
evolutionary path, like many languages (French, for instance, is a
totally Romance language, while Dutch is very much a Germanic language);
it originally came from the Germanic language of the Celts; was later
hybridized with the language of the Vikings (Hi, Orjan!), and after the
Norman invasion it received a lot of influence from Norman French.

As a result, we have some of the grammar forms of the Germanic lanugages
(particularly the Celtic family and the Scandinavian family) as well as
influences from the Romance languages (i.e. French).  In the words used,
also, there is influence from both places--in general, for any one word,
you can find a word that means almost exactly the same thing, with the
other derivation.  For example, "horse-jockey" and "equestrian".  Oddly,
in a lot of cases, the Germanic word is considered "base" or "vulgar",
while the Latinate word is considered "proper".  (Well, not *that*
oddly; the nobility of England was French for many years.)  Thus, for
instance, "piss" vs. "urinate"--the latter is considered the more proper
technical term, and you will _never_ hear a doctor or nurse say the
former (at least not in a professional setting).  Silly, isn't it?

> I could be wrong, of course. I just note that there are Germanic languages
> where both of the above errors are considered correct. But I do not think
> German is one of them. (What is Dutch like?)

There is nothing wrong with the "improper" form, and it really doesn't
fit right in a lot of cases.  You know how I was talking about having an
"ear" for the language?  Well, the form w/o a preposition ending the
sentence just *sounds* wrong in many cases.  Winston Churchill put it
best when he said (and I paraphrase) "That is an error up with which I
shall not put!"

> > Ronald
> 
> Greetings,
> Oerjan.

Vanyel

