ElJefe writes:
>Saltwater wrote:
>> 	As Recordkeepor of the most-transferred currency, I'd like to most
>> humbly point out that things like "i trade in all my points except 10 for
>> Marks", "if CFJ 128 was judged true, i transfer 18 Marks to Oerjan,
>> otherwise I transfer 10 Marks to favor.", and "if Steve won the Game, I
>> transfer all my Points into Marks, then, if I have less Kudos than
>> Morendil, I transfer half of my remaining Marks to the X Group treasury,
>> unless it's Tuesday" are an extraordinary pain.
>
>Well, it's already been pointed out that these things are necessary
>in times of uncertain Gamestate. But they're also quite a common
>move, as when I convert all my Points to Marks. Are you saying that
>I should figure out how many points I have and tell the Scorekeepor?

There is a difference between:
- transfer all my points to X
- if Y then transfer 5 points to X

The first is very easy to program, while the second forces the Scorekeepor
to check back, whether Y happened, which is a real pain and not programmable.

>> said "Hi there. . I'd like to make the following transfer. . if grapes
>> are selling better than grain on the commodities market, transfer half
>> the current balance of my savings account to my checking account, unless
>> the Sonics win their game tonight, in which case only transfer a quarter."
>
>Well, the stock & commodities markets certainly do have their own "game
>custom"  of stop and limit orders. (e.g. "buy 100 shares when the price
>gets down to 60", or "sell 200 oz. of gold today if you can get at least
>385, otherwise don't sell").  One broker told me that the trading floor
>will accept any order that the floor can be made to understand.

But in ElJefe's example the condition is limited to the commodity itself,
while in Saltwater's example the condition is external. Quite a difference!

Ronald

