> I think you are right about German. As good as my German serves me, I come
> to:
> "Dieser ist der Tafel, worauf ich das Buch lege."
> (For those who don't know a single word German, translation word to word gives:
> This is the table, whereon I the book lay."
> 
> To add, the situation in my own mother tongue, dutch, is that both are
> allowed. One can say both:
> "Dit is de tafel, waarop ik het boek leg." en
> "Dit is de tafel, waar ik het boek op leg."
> The first is completely identical to the German, and apart from the fact that
> in a subsidiary sentence the verb is put at the end equal to English. The last
> one translates to:
> "This is the table, where I the book on lay," so indeed comes close to the
> (at least officialy grammatically incorrect) English
> "This is the table, that I lay the book on."
> 
> Andre
> 
> 

After I wrote this I started doubting again. Maybe the second one is not
right after all. But I might be wrong again. Main conclusion is that I don't
know my own dutch grammar after all...

Well, let's see. What if I use another example:
"Here is the man to whom I gave the book."
"Dit is de man aan wie ik het boek gaf." Ok.
"Dit is de man wie ik het boek aan gaf." Ouch! Not even close to sounding
like dutch! So with 'wie' instead of 'waar' it's not split.
By the way, "Dit is de man waaraan ik het boek gaf." is probably incorrect, but
if I heared it I wouldn't notice there was something wrong.

Still the case for not splitting is not very strong, as 'waar' and 'wie' are
not grammatically equivalent:

"To whom did you give the book?"
"Aan wie gaf je het boek?"

"On what did you lay the book?"
"Waarop legde je het boek?" (not split) or "Waar legde je het boek op?" (split)

Doubt, doubt, doubt... Can we split or can't we? We do, that's for sure. And
it can only be done with 'waar' not with 'wie', 'welke' (which), etc.

I look again, and I think it's good after all. Maybe I should just go to the
library and take a book on dutch grammar...

By the way, now we're talking about these kinds of languages anyway, my father
is bilingual since about 2 weeks. The dutch gouvernment (or was it the EEC?)
has officially accepted Nedersaksisch (Ger.: Niedersachsisch, it translates
into English as Lower Saxon) as a minority language. It consists of the
dialects spoken in the northeastern of the Netherlands and northern Germany.

Andre

