This Dissenting Opinion remains unofficial for the time being. For
now, I just want to note that Justice Michael's Judgement is wrong
in at least two places.

Firstly, he has misunderstood the role that R.116 plays in the debate.
Although it is true, as Justice Morendil correctly points out, that
R.116 governs all play and all situations to which its language makes
it relevant, this is not needed in the argument that CFJ 818 is FALSE.
R.116 does not govern the Jurisdictions of Compacts of Organizations
of undefined Class just because it governs all play generally. It does
so because the expansion is 'unprohibited and unregulated', and so is
spoken to directly by the language of R.116.

Secondly, Justice Michael totally ignores the effect of R.1535(iii):

      The Compact of an Organization can specify any or all of the
      following.

      iii) How additional Players enter the Jurisdiction of the
           Compact.  If this is not specified, the Compact cannot
           expand its Jurisdiction.

This serves to strengthen the notion that the expansion of the
Jurisdiction is unprohibited and unregulated, by making it clear
that such an expansion is possible to the extent permitted by
the Rules.

Steve Gardner                     |  "Justice? You get justice in the next
Dept. of Philosophy, Monash Uni.  |   world, in this world you get the law."
gardner@aurora.cc.monash.edu.au   |          --  William Gaddis --

