Wes say:
> > place), there is a distinction between Moves and Events.  
> 
> This is an important distinction. A Move can cause an Event (or fail
> to cause one, if it is an illegal Move). An Event can happen without a
> Move. 

Does anyone remember my Game Stae Modification proto?  The term GSM was
simply awful, but I see a lot of the same ideas popping up... I'll have
to dig that out again sometime.  Essentially, I distinguish three basic
types of GSM: Automatic, Proposed, and Manual.  Automatic GSMs occur
exclusively because of something specified in the Ruleset--usually based
on timing of some sort.  For instance, payment of Salaries would be an
AGSM, as would the end of the Voting Period.  Proposed GSMs would occur
as a direct result of Proposals; i.e. Rule Changes and Directives.
Manual GSMs would occur as a direct result of Player action (in the more
recent terminology, I would say that an MGSM is an Event which is caused
by a Move.)

> > a Move is any action taken by a _person_ (not necessarily a Player,
> > for a very important reason that will become apparent shortly) which
> > causes one or more Events (which may occur before, at the same time
> > as, or after the Move).  
> 
> We would submit that even non-person Entities may make some action which
> must be contrued as a Move, such as Group Votes. Persons are Entities,
> although they are not Game Entities as they have an existance outside
> the Game. 

I disagree.  A Group Vote is an Automatic Event which occurs as a result
of certain Manual Events...

> > Players, because of their dual nature, both as Game Entnties and as
> > beings with existence independent of the Game, are confusing.  i have
> > found that it is best (in terms of the construction of a coherent
> > theory of Moves) to consider a Player to be a Game Entity "magically"
> > associated with one (or possibly more than one) person.  this
> > association is part of what allows a given ecto-Game action to cause
> > endo-Game Events.  there's at least one case where ecto-Game actions
> > by persons not associated with any Player can cause an Event, and that
> > is when a person who is not already a Player registers to become one.
> > this Move causes a number of Events to take place, the most
> > significant of which is the creation of the association between the
> > person and a Player that gives that person the broadened scope of
> > power to cause Events that characterizes Players.  note that all
> > persons have some limited power to cause Events; persons who happen to
> > be Players merely have (significantly) more power to do so.  again,
> > the Rules have complete control over the ability of Moves to cause
> > Events.
> 
> That would be one theory, but we would prefer to think of Players as a
> sub-set of persons who have the ability to cause certain Events within
> the Game. A Player is not a Game Entity, per se, since a Player will
> exist outside the Game. However, the status of a Player is a Game
> Entity, since that status has meaning only within Nomic. A person is
> determined to be a Player when that person is Registered as described in
> the Rules. 

This is somewhat contrary to the prevailing theory...  as I recall, the
recent consensus was that the Player was the Agoran Entity, and the
person the RL entity, and the Rules described a direct mapping of one to
the other.  This is why a Player can remain contiguous through
dereregistration cycles.

Vanyel

