Wes say:
> > Ah, you have a randomized .sig, too?
> 
> Not really; we manually append them to the end of our documents. :r in
> vi. We're still not UNIX guru enough to actually randomize it, and still
> allow us to use our business .sig for all of our business oriented mail.
> We don't suppose you would know how to select a .sig sometimes, and have
> the computer randomly select one the rest of the time, would you? It
> would be most helpful. We could even Kudo you (which would seem to be
> the proper spelling of the verb. <insert huge smiley here>).  

The way *I* do it:

I have in my .exrc file the following line:

map = 6dd:!fort.perl:r ~/.sig


What this does: first, it deletes the six lines starting with the line
the cursor is on.  Then it runs the program called "fort.perl".  Then it
reads in the file "~/.sig".  See, I have a program called "fort.perl",
which I wrote, which runs the "fortune" program until it gets a fortune
of three lines or less.  Then, it prints to the file ~/.sig a blank
line, followed by the top line of my sig (the -=-=-=- one), another
blank line, and the three-line fortune.  I have my mailer set up so that
it always prints a "--" at the end of each message, followed by the
contents of the file ~/.sig, which is always six lines long.  Then, to
sign a message, I use the appropriate name depending on the destination
(Vanyel, Don, etc.), then go to the blank line immediately below and hit
the equal sign and press enter.  This gives me a new random sig.  If it
is inappropriate, I repeat until I get something appropriate.

Complicated, I know... but neat!

Vanyel

