>Little known Agora fact #4872:
>Actually, legal precedent requires that whenever the datestamp of a
>listserver post is questionable, the date to go with is _not_ the Date:
>header, but rather the header which indicates when the _listserver_
>received the post.  I should know, I judged that CFJ. :)

Um, but wasn't that *one specific* Rule which said for a certain
type of message, the date of the message was the Date:, so long
as it was to the knowledge of the sender dated accurately within
5 minutes?  And since that applied only to the specific sort of
message which that Rule dealt with, it would *not* apply to all messages
in general?

Could you dig up that CFJ and post it?  I'd be interested in seeing it.

Chuck

