Date: Wed, 15 Nov 1995 12:58:57 -0500
From: jlc@triple-i.com (Jeff Caruso)
Message-Id: <9511151758.AA15057@zeus.Camex.COM>
To: nomic-discussion@teleport.com
Subject: Thoughts on Game Custom
Sender: owner-nomic-discussion@teleport.com
Precedence: bulk
Reply-To: nomic-discussion@teleport.com
Status: RO

This article explores the many meta-rules and understandings involved 
in Agora Nomic, sometimes referred to as "Game Custom". These are custom
of behavior or of perception that the players all try to follow.  In 
situations where not all players are following the same custom, the
Nomic dispute-resolution procedures are required.

Some of these are not just Game Custom but are actually part of the Rules.
Obviously I'm not including the entire Ruleset, but I will point out
some Rule-based customs that seem important.

Obviously these are just my own understanding.  However, I have hopes 
that this reflects actual Game Custom in most cases, even where I
prefer it were otherwise.  Where I have specific enough preferences,
I've indicated it in "recommendations".

----------------------------------
Construction of Rules.  Rules are construed according to their
meaning and not according to their intent.  They govern all aspects
of the game collectively and not in isolation.  Words explicitly
defined in the Rules have the defined meaning; words not so defined
are usually interpreted according to their ordinary meaning.

RECOMMENDATION:  Settle by Rule or CFJ the status of words making up
"phrases of art", e.g. not explicitly defined but obviously used in a 
special manner in the Ruleset.

----------------------------------
Creation of Entities.  Agora consists of the Rules and other entities
coming under the purview of the Rules.  Any such entity either exists 
independently of the Rules, or is created by the Rules and of a "type"
created by the Rules.  Types are distinct.  Created entities only exist 
if created in accordance with the Rules.

----------------------------------
Destruction of Entities.  An entity created in accordance with the Rules 
ceases to exist when there is (for a period of time) no Rule referring to 
that Type of entity.

----------------------------------
Modification of Entities. An entity created under the Rules has continuing
existence until destroyed, either explicitly or by virtue of the Destruction
metarule.  In particular, if the Rules referring to that Type of entity are
modified, then the entity is itself modified to conform to the new Rules.

Attributes, designations, and states under the Rules also have this kind of
continuity, continuing in effect until changed in accordance with the Rules.

RECOMMENDATION:  Settle by Rule or CFJ what happens when the Rules are so 
modified that some features of the entity or attribute cannot be determined 
from the new Rules.

----------------------------------
Game state.  This is the status of all Rules and all entities coming under 
the purview of the Rules.

----------------------------------
Game move.  This is an action of some sort taking place under the Rules
and at least potentially having some effect on the Game state in accordance
with the Rules.

----------------------------------
Time limits.  If the Rules require a Player to perform some action (or Game 
move), but do not specify a time limit, then the player cannot be charged
with a violation of the Rule by neglecting the action.

RECOMMENDATION:  Allow a CFJ that such a move has been delayed unreasonably.
Then if the move is an automatic one, the Judge could declare that it was 
already made.  If it was a pragmatic one, then the Judge could appoint a 
Receiver to make it in the Player's place.

----------------------------------
Names.  A player may be referred to by any unambiguous name by which they 
are generally known.  If a player announces to all players that they wish 
to use another nickname, and this is unambiguous, then the player may be
referred to by that name.  The same string may in fact be two different
names if it is used in different contexts. (e.g. The Nomic Potato)

----------------------------------
Registration.  A player is a person registered to play.  A person may only
be one Player.  If a player leaves the Game and returns, they are still 
the same Player.

A corporate person could nominate a person to represent them as 
a Player in the Game, provided that person was not otherwise registered 
as a Player.  The terms of this representation would be enforced by extra-
Game agreement.

RECOMMENDATION:  Settle by Rule or CFJ the status of corporate Players 
within the game.

----------------------------------
Voting.  Certain game moves require "voting" by the Players.  A vote is 
customarily a game move that occurs when the vote is sent, but it may
be changed during the voting period.  This change has the effect of 
cancelling the old vote and substituting for it the new vote at the 
new time.  Thus players leaving the Game may vote before doing so, 
(but not change their vote after leaving), and players new to the 
Game may vote immediately.

RECOMMENDATION:  Restrict voting to those who were Players at the beginning
of the Voting Period.

----------------------------------
Permitted versus possible.  Rule 116 says that things are permitted if not
forbidden.  It does not necessarily mean that they can be made to happen
by chanting "abracadabra" in the Public Forum or elsewhere.

----------------------------------
Rule to obey the rules.  Rule 101 says "obey the rules".  It does not 
follow that if it is repealed we may break the Rules.

----------------------------------
Conditional actions.  Customarily, conditional moves are allowed, such as
"If xxx then I transfer NN points to Player yyy.  Otherwise, I don't"
and take full effect.  The effect of more obscure and involved conditionals
is not settled game custom.

----------------------------------
Time-delayed actions.  Customarily, time-delayed moves are allowed, such as
"I transfer NN points to player yyy, effective on dd-mmm-yy at hh:mm" and 
take full effect as of the time named.  Such moves can be extra work for 
the Officers, however, and are usually used only when the exact timing of 
an event is important, such as in a Scam.

----------------------------------
Retroactive actions.  Customarily it is not possible for any game move 
to change the game state as of a previous point in time.  CFJ's do not 
change a prior game state, though they may discover new facts about it 
that were not apparent before.

----------------------------------
Timing of obligations.  If a player is obligated to perform some game move
or action upon certain conditions, the obligation begins as soon as the 
conditions take effect, and is discharged when the required move is made.
Additional obligations to perform the same game move do not require additional
instances of the move, though some obligations are additive in nature and
are not regarded as the "same" game move.

The case of obligations that recur weekly is unsettled.

RECOMMENDATION:  If a player is obliged to perform an obligation weekly, 
the obligation begins at the beginning of the week.  In particular a new 
Rule creating such an obligation does not oblige a player during the 
remainder of the week in which the new Rule takes effect.

FURTHER RECOMMENDATION:  If a player is obliged to perform an obligation 
weekly or during some other time limit, and the Rule is repealed or amended 
so as to no longer so obligate the player, then the obligation is cancelled.
However, if the obligation or the time limit is modified before it is 
discharged, then the player is still obligated under the modified form of 
the Rule within the time limit.

----------------------------------
Official Duties.  If a Player is obligated to perform certain actions, as 
a result of a designation or of holding a position under the Rules, then 
if another Player is so designated or holds the position in the player's
stead, the obligation is transferred to the new Player.  If a player 
ceases to hold the designation or position for any reason, and no other
player takes their place, then nobody is responsible for fulfilling the
obligation.

----------------------------------
Platonic versus Pragmatic.  Game moves that are purely retractible, 
(such as a Point transfer) are simply without effect if found to be
illegal.  Game moves that are at least partly non-retractible may incur
a sanction but otherwise have whatever effects they are bound to have.

----------------------------------
Secret rules.  Players cannot be subject to Rules or laws that are unknown
to them.  Similarly, entities which are non-disclosable to players who must
make judgements with respect to them, cannot have any effect on the Game state.

----------------------------------
Automatic actions by Officers.  Officers are simply recordkeepers.  Unless
otherwise explicitly worded, any event taking place under authority of an 
Office, involving pure game entities, is deemed to have taken place when 
the Rules empower it, without any separate action of the Officer.

----------------------------------
Definition of Proposal.  A Proposal is now anything so designated.

RECOMMENDATION:  Do this for CFJs.

----------------------------------
Incorrect reports.  If a player is required to publish a portion of the 
game state, errors in the report are not a violation of the Rules, but
are dealt with via Claims of Error.

----------------------------------
Randomness.  Some actions are purely unverifiable.  Like randomness, or
truth in advertising.

RECOMMENDATION:  keep these to a minimum.

----------------------------------
Disclosure and secrecy.  Certain items are designated as privileged and
may not be disclosed.  Certain items are so sensitive that knowledge of them
may not even be used (like people's vote) to the advantage of the person
so knowing.  (This is another almost-purely-unverifiable.)

----------------------------------
The "sending" of messages.  In an e-mail based game, Rules referring to
a message "sent" from a Player to a Player, refer to the moment it leaves
the control of the player with the normal expectation that it will reach
its intended destination.  This can be the case even if the message passes
through the hands of other persons, and even if it turns out to be impossible
for the message to actually reach its destination.

----------------------------------
Crises.  Certain times are referred to as "crises", when there is a
disagreement about the Game State.  These are resolved through the usual
conflict-resolution mechanism (CFJs).  More serious is the case where there
is a conflict involving the mechanism for resolving disagreements itself,
or in which the Ruleset as a whole appears broken.

RECOMMENDATION: Create a "Reconstituting" mechanism deeply entrenched in 
the Rules, such as:

  Proposal (MI=4)
  Nomic Firewall
      
  Create a rule that reads as follows:
      
      If a Player believes that the Rules are hopelessly broken, e may
      send in a Public Message a Proposition that the Rules be replaced,
      including a Proposed Replacement Ruleset.
      
      Such a Proposition is adopted if at least 10 Players, comprising at 
      least a majority of all players, approve or reject it in a Public 
      Message within 10 days of the posting of the Proposition, with no
      Speaker rejecting it, and with at least 4 times as many Players
      approving as rejecting during the entire 10-day period.  Otherwise 
      it is not adopted.
      
      If the Proposition is adopted:
      
        1. First, all Rules except this one are automatically repealed.
      
        2. Next, for each Proposed Rule in the Proposition, a Rule is 
           created with the indicated text, and numbered with the 
           indicated number.  If the Proposed Replacement Ruleset 
           grants other properties to Rules, (for example Mutable/
           Immutable status), then those properties are specified 
           for each Rule as indicated in the Proposition.  All these 
           creations and specifications happen simultaneously.
      
      For purposes of this Rule: 

        1. a Public Message is any message to all Players, or to any 
           list server or other mechanism most recently designated as 
           a Public Forum in accordance with the Rules.
      
        2. a Player is anyone listed as a Player in an official report 
           during the previous month, or who has subsequently become a 
           Player in accordance with the Rules.
      
        3. a "Speaker" is anyone listed as Speaker in an official report 
           during the previous month.
      
        4. an official report is a report sent to all Players, or to all 
           persons reasonably believed at the time to be players, and sent 
           under authority of the Rules, or reasonably believed by the 
           sender to be sent under authority of the Rules, during the 
           previous month.
      
      This rule takes precedence over all other Rules.


Regards,


- elJefe

******************************************************************
  Dr. Jeffrey L. Caruso <jlc@triple-i.com>
  Information International

