From: gb485@cleveland.Freenet.Edu (Steven A Swiniarski)
To: nomic-business@teleport.com
Subject: BUS: PROTO:More Rule Numbering
Sender: owner-nomic-business@teleport.com
Precedence: bulk
Reply-To: nomic-discussion@teleport.com
Status: RO

PROTO: Title and Section Numbers for Rules

(Yet another Proto inspired by the comment, "it couldn't be done." This
 time in reaction to my Rule Numbering Proto.  This, in fact, is a revised
 version of my first Proposal "Indexing the Logical Ruleset," which
 I still think is a good idea-- though the idea is much better written
 now :)

Let the Following Rule be Created (Title Number of Rules):

     Each Category of the Logical Ruleset shall have associated with it
     a unique Title Number.  Such Title Numbers shall be integers
     greater than zero. The Rulekeepor shall give each
     newly-created Category a Title Number when it is created.  The
     Title Number given to a Category shall be the least integer greater
     than all other Title Numbers previously given to a Category.
     Once a Category has been given a Title Number, it shall not be
     changed except as specified in the Rules.

     Upon adoption of this Rule, Initial Title Numbers shall be applied
     by the Rulekeepor to the existing Categories of the Logical
     Ruleset. These Title Numbers shall be applied to the existing
     Categories, in the order they appear in the Logical Ruleset. Once
     all existing Categories are so Numbered, this paragraph shall
     repeal itself.

     All Rules within a specific Category have the same Title Number
     as that Category.

{Comment: Title Number might be confused with Rule Titles, if so we can    
dispense with the strict legalism of "Title" and call this a Category Number.  
This language is based on a more-or-less strict analogy with Rule Numbers}

Let the following Rule be created (Section Number of Rules):

     Each Rule has associated with it a Section Number denoting its
     relative position within its Category.  Such Section Numbers shall
     be integers greater than zero. The Rulekeepor shall give each
     newly-created Rule a Section Number when it is created.  The
     Rulekeepor shall give a Rule a new Section Number whenever the
     Category of that Rule is changed. The Section Number given to a
     Rule shall be the least integer greater than all other Section
     Numbers previously given to a Rule within the Category in which the
     Rule appears.  Once a Rule has been given a Section Number, it
     shall not be changed except as specified in this and other Rules.
 
     Upon adoption of this Rule, Initial Section Numbers shall be
     applied by the Rulekeepor to the existing Rules within the Logical
     Ruleset. These Section Numbers shall be applied to the existing
     Rules, one Category at a time, in the order of Numerical precedence
     (ignoring precedence claims within the Rules themselves.) Once
     all existing Rules are so Numbered, this paragraph shall repeal
     itself.


Let the following Rule be Created (Referencing by Title and Section Numbers)

     It shall be an unambiguous way to specify a Rule by referring to it
     by its Title and Section Numbers.  Such a specification must
     include both Numbers in the form XXX.YYY, where XXX is the Title
     Number and YYY is the Section Number.  This Rule takes precedence
     over any Rule that would invalidate this method of referring to
     Rules.

{Comment: At the moment, all this will do is make it a tad easier to
          find a Rule in the Logical Ruleset (each Rule would have a
          Number pointing to its category.)  However, this is a step
          toward kelly's suggestion of a full-blown tiered system.
          Consider, once each rule is so numbered, we  could dispense
          with Rule Numbers as such with a few amendments to the
          precedence rules. (The reason I worded the initial Section
          Numbering so.) Of course it's a little more complex than this,
          we'd want to reorganize Categories and legislate a means to
          change their Title Numbers, at the very least, before we base
          precedence, even partially, on Category, but in the long run,
          with a logical set up to the Categories, it might actually
          make more sense than the current system.}
   



--
Steven Swiniarski  (aka S Andrew Swann)
gb485@cleveland.freenet.edu
Whenever you have an efficient government you have a dictatorship.
                                        --Harry S Truman

