On Wed, 22 Nov 1995, Steve Gardner wrote:

> Orjan Johansen writes:
> >Not that I can see. Should that last "properties" be "entities", maybe?
> 
> Hm. Thinking about it more, I think Vanyel's use of "Entity" tripped
> me up. The proto doesn't talk about Entities. I think that's probably
> the best thing about it. I'm not thinking of the properties referred
> to above as Entities at all. If anything, Entities are to be thought
> as being defined out of properties themselves. I guess this is kind
> of a Humean, or Buddhist metaphysics: all things (entities, states,
> relations etc) are just bundles of properties.

But if an entity is just a bundle of properties, it follows that an 
entity before a change is not the same entity as the entity after a change.
Thus, entities cannot be changed at all. Which may very well be what 
those metaphysics conclude, but certainly not appropriate for Agora.

In fact, existence being a property cannot make sense if an 
entity is not something beside its properties.

> So Vanyel was both wrong and right in a way: wrong, because the proto
> doesn't assume anything about Entities in particular. If existence
> is assumed to be property of Entities, then the creation and destruction
> of Entities will, sure enough, count as an event. If not, then not.
> But he's right because I think as a matter of fact we *do* think 
> intuitively, of existence as a kind of property. (It's only philosophical
> reflection that highlights some of the problems with doing so.)

_Only_ philosophical reflection? You may be able to sweep philosophy 
under the rug if you never think about abstract concepts, but not while 
playing Agora!

> And therefore we do think, intuitively, of the creation and destruction
> of Entities as fairly prototypical events. 

Events, yes, but not necessarily changes of properties.

Please don't formulate your Proposals in such a way as to depend on
unresolved philosophical issues. Resolve them in the Proposal, if
necessary. (We all love metaphysical Rules, don't we?)

Greetings,
Oerjan.

