Kelly Martin was heard to say:
> Wes> Therefore, a CFJ which alleges that an action which has not taken place
> Wes> yet (and is therefore not a Move) is not a legal CFJ and cannot be
> Wes> legally Judged. 
> 
> as i believe Steve pointed out, such a CFJ could be construed as one of
> the form "The Rules should be interpreted such that..."

Yes, but this is a seperate and distinct Entity from a CFJ in the form
"This Move is illegal". In fact, one creates Blots if Judged TRUE, while
the other does not. 

> my recent exploration of the underlying metaphysics of the Game lead
> me to believe that Rule 662 is poorly constructed.  i need to revise
> my Judicial Reform protoproposal and get it back into circulation..

Depending on your point of view. We define the underlying metaphysics of
the Game according to the Rules in existance at the time, rather than
the ideal situation. May be suggest a Rule which creates another term
for all possible moves which may be made, and maintain "Move" as the
term for moves which have been made? We believe that Move has already
been absorbed by the Rule Set and would require major invasive surgery
to change it's meaning. There are bound to be complications... 

> Wes> It causes the Event of creating a condition within the Game in which a
> Wes> CFJ alleging that said Move is illegal is a legal Move. 
> 
> exactly what Game Entity is this Event modifying?

None, but it allows for the creation of an Entity which was not legal to
create before. If such an action is not considered to be an Event, then
we need to rethink the whole system again, else there are going to be
many loopholes... 

> Wes> They are a Nomic Entity, but the are not a Game Entity. The difference
> Wes> is that Players tend to exist outside the Nomic universe; they have a
> Wes> life, so to speak. They *may* be changed by actions not specified in the
> Wes> Rules. For example, we may go get a haircut; it's not specified in the
> Wes> Rules, and it changes a Player (us), but luckily we are not a Game
> Wes> Entity.
> 
> again, here we run into a difference of opinion about the nature of
> Players.  i believe that when you (Wes Contreras) get a haircut, that
> in no way affects the Nomic Entity Wes, because the person Wes
> Contreras is not identical with the Player Wes.  there is (merely a
> correspondance between the two.
> 
> this position avoids having to grant Entity status to properties, as
> you do below.  properties are not themselves Entities, because
> Entities are things which have existence in and of themselves.
> "green" is not an entity (although "greenness" might be).

Perhaps it's just a difference of opinion upon the definition of Entity.
We use entity in general to describe the existance of any single thing,
whether it be tangible or intangible. A Nomic Entity is an entity which
can be affected by or affects the Game of Nomic. Oftentimes, we say
"Entity" when we intend to indicate a Nomic Entity, since it's usually
common sense whether it applies in Nomic or not. 

Game Entity on the other hand is a term defined by the Rules as those
Entities which are defined and affected ONLY within the Game. Thus, Game
Entities are a subset of Nomic Entities. For example, we consider
Players to be a Nomic Entity, although not a Game Entity. Groups, on the
other hand, have no existance outside Nomic, therefore they are a Game
Entity. 

Greem would not be an Entity because green is an adjective; an Entity
must by definition be a noun. Greenness may be, depending on its usage,
since Greenness is a condition which may exist in any number of
situations and thus could be considered to have a seperate existance
from the object which one is using to describe as possessing Greenness.

A good parallel would be an email address. We would consider an email
address to be an Entity, although not a Game Entity. It is a thing (a
collection of characters with a special significance) and it has an
independant existance (it can be changed without directly affecting 
anything else). It is a Nomic Entity, since it affects the Game, but
it's not a Game Entity, since it exists outside the confines of the
Rules. If it were somehow included as a Game Entity, then it would be
illegal to change or affect one's email address except as allowed for in
the Rules. Bad ju-jus. 

> Wes> Now the status of a Player, and various other conditions which
> Wes> are attached to a Player, *are* Game Entities, such as Membership
> Wes> in a Group, Patent Titles, etc., and these are under the
> Wes> jurisdiction of Rule 1011.
> 
> another matter i am in no way convinced of.

Which part? 

> >> i've never been very comfortable with 1011, yet i haven't thought of a
> >> good way to fix it.  sooner or later, i'll come up with something.
> 
> Wes> What's wrong with it? Anything which does not exist solely within the
> Wes> Game should be able to be modified outside the Game. 
> 
> that's not the problem i have with Rule 1011.

What is? 



Enjoy!

