Steve sez:
>            It sounds as if you want to assert the existence of
> something more fundamental, or at least something different than, an
> entity's properties - something in which the entity's properties
> actually inhere.

Yes.  At the core of an Entity, there is a non-Property thing, which I
keep wanting to call "its entity", except that seems to be a circular
argument.  Perhaps "its existence" would be better, I'm not sure.  But
basically it's this: Properties can not, in and of themselves, exist.
They can only exist insofar as they are possessed by an Entity.  Thus an
Entity is more than "just a bundle of properties"; it has something else
at its core, which is totally nondescript (as soon as it becomes
distinct, it is possessing properties) yet unique.  It is this which
remains the same throughout the existence of the Entity, though
properties may change radically, and it is the uniqueness of this which
prevents otherwise identical Entities from being "the same".  Am I
making sense?

>                  My continental philosophy is pretty weak, but I
> think Heidegger might have called that Dasein, or Being.

Sure, that works.  "Dasein"... I like that.

