PROTO: Agoraspace v2.1

Let the following Rule be created (Agoraspace):

     The Agoraverse is the virtual multidimensional space of infinite 
     extent and dimension in which exist all Entities defined in the
     Ruleset, other than the Agoraverse itself.  Agoraspace is that
     subset of the Agoraverse that adheres to Euclidean geometry.  
     All Entities, other than Agoraspace, exist within the bounds of 
     Agoraspace, unless explicitly permitted otherwise by the Rules.

     There is a specific mathematical point within Agoraspace known as 
     the Origin.  All references to location within Agoraspace shall be 
     made with reference to the Origin, explicitly or implicitly.

     All Entities within Agoraspace, whose location is otherwise 
     unspecified, are located at the Origin. The Origin is, at all 
     times, a permissible location for an Entity to exist.

{Comment:  The base of the pyramid which generally defines the core of
           the idea, and permitting favor's infinite dimensionally w/o 
           getting out of hand about it.  Gives a default location for 
           everything to orbit around.

           v2.1-- for kelly, rewrote this whole thing, allowing for the
           possibility for non-Euclidean spaces to exist in a wider 
           Agoraverse.  Also, I rewrote this so the Origin isn't 
           hardwired into the definition of space, so we don't, 
           necessarily, have to have a preferential reference frame the 
           Origin is simply the reference point now, and the coord. 
           system will be defined in terms of the origin, not vice 
           versa. Note, this will probably be the only place I mention
           "point" in terms of geometry, the potential for confusion is 
           just too great.}

Let the following rule be created (Coordinates in Agoraspace):

     When no other means of specifying a location exists within 
     Agoraspace, the location shall be specified in terms of a Cartesian 
     coordinate system whose axes are fixed relative to the Origin.  The 
     values of all coordinates in this system shall be zero at the 
     Origin.  When the Rules refer to an X, Y, or Z axis, they shall be
     the first three axes of this coordinate system.

{Comment: v2.1-- I need a fixed Cartesian system for some of my later
                 rules, but it's now defined to not be the exclusive
                 coordinate system, or to be preferential. Now the
                 Origin could move, rotate, accelerate, and these Rules
                 wouldn't be affected.}


Let the following Rule be created (Units of Measure):

     The official unit of linear measure within Agoraspace is the cimon.  
     All measurements of distance in Agoraspace shall be made in cimon.  
     SI prefixes can be used to specify larger or smaller distances 
     without ambiguity.  (1 kilocimon = 1000 cimons = 1,000,000 
     milicimons.)  All Entities within Agoraspace extend zero cimons in
     all dimensions unless explicitly defined otherwise in the Rules.

     The official unit of angular measure within Agoraspace is the 
     agorad. Agorads divide a circumference into one-thousandths.
     (1 agorad = 0.36 degrees.)

{Comment: Since no one has yet drafted a full coordinate system for
          Agora, I guess it's not surprising that everyone forgot a unit
          of measure. 

          v2.1-- kelly suggested a different name for the units, so I
          came up with "cimon" which actually sounds somewhat elegant,
          as well as sounding like a unit of measure.  I pronounce it
          "simon." (For those of you who haven't noticed, it's "nomic"
          backwards.)  I've also moved the definition of agorad here &
          changed the name of the rule since I've dumped the quantizing
          idea. (Note: I've squashed the capitals for you Oerjan.)
          I also changed the default entity size to zero, so they'll
          "fit" within whatever surface they're confined in. (also so
          they're aren't occupying undefined dimensions by accident.)}


Let the following Rule be created (The Cartographor):

     There is an Office known as the Cartographor.  The Cartographor is 
     the Officer in charge of maintaining a general record of Agoraspace 
     as well as the coordinates of all Players.

     Every other Nomic Week, the Cartographor is required to generate a 
     Map of Agoraspace, as defined in other Rules.  However, whatever 
     other Rules may Require, the Map must contain the following 
     coordinates:

       i) Those of every Player.
      ii) Those of every Entity whose coordinates are not at the Origin.
     iii) Those of every Entity that the Rules require the Cartographor 
          to maintain the coordinates of.

     The Cartographor's salary shall be four points.

{Comment: Yes, its another @#$%& Officer.  What can I say, someone has
          to do all the recordkeeping.

          v2.1-- Fixed the spelling goof and the missing "as."}


Let the following Rule be created (Bounding Agoraspace):

     All Entities in Agoraspace shall only exist at those locations, 
     or sets of locations, wherein the Rules expressly give permission 
     for those Entities to exist.  Within such boundaries, all Entities 
     which are permitted to exist at a location may all coexist at 
     that coordinate without limit.

     All Entities, except Players, change their location-- or have 
     their location change-- only as permitted by the Rules.  If the 
     Rules are silent as to the movement of an Entity or type of Entity, 
     such an Entity cannot move. Players can change their location in 
     any way not expressly forbidden by the Rules, by sending a message 
     detailing the movement to the Cartographor.

{Comment: More default restrictions.  Without one of the following
          rules, this effectively restricts everything to the Origin.
          It allows Entities to coexist as a default and allows Players
          to move as they wish (within the Rules) while limiting all
          other Entities to only move as permitted.
          
          v2.1-- kelly pointed out that more than one set of coordinates
          can refer to the same point (location) so I reworded the Rule.
          I personally prefer allowing the permissive model for Player
          movement.  It would be interesting having Players joyride
          around while the Rules are being drafted.  (someone might get
          stranded even :)} 

======================================================================

Three Options for the "Surface" of Agora.

Wonder of wonders, I did all of these without once resorting to
mathematical notation.  Needless to say, the three options become
progressively more complex while remaining, essentially, two
dimensional.

(Actually, the sphere and torus are sort of 2.1 dimensional, since the
Origin is always included in places to be, even if it isn't on the
surface, and I am *not* going to go to the hassle of defining these
surfaces so the Origin is on the surface.)


Option #1-------------------------------------------------------------
Let the following rule be created (The Agoradisk):

     The Agoradisk is a two dimensional disk centered on the Origin.  It 
     lies on the XY plane and its radius is one kilocimon.  Entities 
     within Agoraspace are constrained to exist only within the 
     locations contained within the Agoradisk.

     Locations within the Agoradisk can be specified by at least one
     pair of coordinates.  The first coordinate is the location's
     longitude, which is an angle measured clockwise around the disk 
     from the positive X axis.  The second coordinate is the location's 
     latitude, which is the location's linear distance from the Origin.

{Comment: This is the simplest bounded space to talk about, a circle
          floating in empty space.

          v2.1--I borrowed kelly's wording, to an extent.  I still want
          the 2d surface floating within an existing Nd space.  I also
          think if we define the place, we should also define a
          coordinate system to go with it.  Changed the name of the
          thing to Agoradisk per _many_ requests.  Changed the surface
          references to polar coords.}


Option #2--------------------------------------------------------------
Let the following rule be created (The Agorasphere):

     The Agorasphere is the surface of a three dimensional sphere
     centered on the Origin.  The Agorasphere intersects the X, Y and Z
     axes, and has a radius of one kilocimon. Entities within Agoraspace
     are constrained to exist only within the locations contained within
     the Agorasphere, or the Origin.

     The circle where the XY plane Z = 0 intersects the Agorasphere is 
     the Equator.  The location where the positive Z axis intersects the
     Agorasphere is the North Pole. The location where the negative
     Z axis intersects the Agorasphere is the South Pole.

     All locations upon the Agorasphere can be specified by at least one 
     pair of coordinates. The first coordinate is the location's 
     longitude, which is an angle measured clockwise from the positive X 
     axis.  The second coordinate is the location's latitude, which is 
     measured from the positive Z axis to the negative Z axis.

{Comment: This is complex, despite its apparent simplicity.  Calculating
          distances requires a conversion to Cartesian coordinates, and
          (as worded) all minimal-distance travel routes must be on
          great circles.  If you're interested, the Agorasphere has
          about 12.6 million square cimons to compare with Agoaplane's
          3.1 million.  If I calculated everything right, the separation
          between parallels is 2pi cimons.

          v2.1--Again, I used kelly's language, to an extent.  I also
          fixed a confusion as to location vs. coordinate.  I simplified
          the language a lot, and ended up with a shorter rule.}

Option #3--------------------------------------------------------------
Let the following rule be created (The Agorus):

     The Agorus is the surface of a three dimensional torus centered on 
     the Origin and the Z axis.  The Agorus intersects the XY plane, has 
     a major radius of one kilocimon, and a minor radius of one-half 
     kilocimon.  (The Agorus' surface is that generated by rotating a 
     base circle completely around the Z axis.  This base circle lies in 
     the XZ plane, is one-half kilocimon in radius, and is centered on 
     the point upon the X axis one kilocimon away from the Origin in the 
     positive X direction.) Entities within Agoraspace are constrained 
     to exist only within the locations contained within the Agorus, or 
     the Origin.

     The circles where the XY plane Z = 0 intersects the Agorus are 
     known as the Equators.  The smaller is the Inner Equator (radius = 
     one-half kilocimon.)  The larger is the Outer Equator (radius = one 
     and one-half kilocimon.)  The circle on Agorus where Z = +0.5 
     kilocimons is the North Parallel.  The circle on Agorus where Z = -
     0.5 kilocimons is the South Parallel.

     All locations upon the Agorasphere can be specified by at least one 
     pair of coordinates. The first coordinate is the location's 
     longitude, which is an angle measured clockwise from the positive X 
     axis.  The second coordinate is the location's latitude, which is 
     an angle measured around Agorus' circular cross-section starting 
     from the North Parallel, towards the Outer Equator.

{Comment: There's popular demand for a torus, so here one is. This looks
          almost as complex as it is, but I managed to do it without
          resorting to one long equation.  (I happen to be writing a
          novel about a toroidal planet.)  This has a surface area of
          19.7 million square cimons.  I don't even want to think about
          calculating distances on the surface.  (And just imagine the
          headaches the gravity in my novel is giving me) The 
          separation between parallels is half that on Agorasphere.
          (Equal to pi cimons.) 

          v2.1-- ditto everything I said about Agorasphere here.}


