I've just revised, and sent, my Agoraspace PROTO taking into account various
comments.  Having worked out the three basic options for an Agora surface, I
came up with a very bizzare thought-- why need the three options be
mutually exclusive?  (kelly, this is why embedded spaces are useful, the
following idea couldn't be implemented w/o embedding Agora in a larger
multidimentional space.)

Consider the great Agorasphere, a spherical surface centered on the origin.
_Within that surface_ we inscribe Agorus, the toroidal surface, and incribe it
so that it's Outer Equator occupies the exact same circle as Agorasphere's
Equator.  Then we fill the hole in the Agorus, with the Agoradisk, so that
 the circle that describes Agoradisk's outer perimeter is exactly the same
as the Inner Equator of the Agorus. . .

The cross section would look like this:

                   ******
                 *        *     * = The surface of Agorasphere
                *          *    @ = The surface of Agorus
               * @@@    @@@ *   - = The surface of Agoradisk
               *@   @  @   @*   # = Where you can travel from 
               #    ~--~    #       Agorus to Agorasphere and vice versa
               *@   @  @   @*   ~ = Where you can travel from
               * @@@    @@@ *       Agoradisk to Agorus and vice versa
                *          *
                 *        *
                   ******


Just a thought...
maybe not :)

Swann

