"Don" == Don Blaheta <blahedo@quincy.edu> writes:

Don> A note on coordinate systems: For non-hyperbolic spaces (they get
Don> really weird, we probably don't want to deal with them), 

you should say Euclidean; there are spaces that are far more confusing
than hyperbolic which aren't hyperbolic.  :)

Don> you need one coordinate for each dimension represented.  At least
Don> one coordinate must be magnitudinal (i.e. specify some distance).
Don> The others may be angular.  If _all_ are magnitudinal, that is
Don> referred to as a Cartesian coordinate system.  

a basis is Cartesian if and only if the unit vectors are orthonormal.
one can have a basis which fully descibes the space, where the axes
are not mutually orthogonal.  such a basis is not Cartesian (but is
still a basis).

of course, polar, cylindrical, and spherical coordinates are not
linear, so it's not meaningful to discuss their unit vectors or
whether or not they are orthonormal.

the most general way i've encountered to describe the location of an
point in n-space is to have n families of surfaces of codimension 1.
each family must completely fill the space, and not intersect each
other (except possibly in a finite number of points).  a point is then
described by the (unique) set formed by choosing one surface from each
of these n families such that those surfaces all intersect only in
that one point.

to illustrate: Cartesian coordinates in 2-space use the family of
vertical lines and the family of horizontal lines.  polar coordinates
in 2-space use the family of circles centered on the origin and the
family of rays eminating from the origin.  spherical coordinates in
3-space use the family of spheres centered on the origin, and two
families of half-planes (one corresponding to each angular parameter).
cylindrical coordinates use the family of right circular cylinders
centered on the z axis, the family of planes perpendicular to the z
axis, and the family of half-planes where the z-axis forms the
boundary of each half-plane.

obviously, there are an infinitude of other possibile coordinizations
of n-space.  the standard ones are only used because they are
convenient and/or obvious.

coordinizating spaces of infinite dimension is more complicated, and i
don't want to get into it.  bases of infinite dimension are
unpleasant.

i have never actually seen anyone use a non-linear coordinization of a
space of dimension greater than 3.

k.
--
kelly martin                                 <kelly@poverty.bloomington.in.us>

