Precedence: bulk
Reply-To: nomic-discussion@teleport.com
Status: RO

Vanyel sez to Steve:

> I realize that my opinion is not universally held, yes, but that's true
> of pretty much whatever I say.  Obviously, it is only my opinion when I
> assert the existence of a fundamental, and as you can guess I have read
> no formal philosophy on the matter, but I really don't think properties
> can exist alone... they _must_ be possessed by something else.  When I
> say, "that book is red", does "red" have existence?  No, the book _is_
> red.  Of course, the irony that I am arguing this with a philosopher
> does not escape me. :)

Oh, one of the things I like about philosophy is that by definition, 
it doesn't require formal schooling. It's supposed to be something 
you can do on your own. :)

One does not have to be a philosopher, for instance, to reflect that 
'redness' can be a distinct complex of things that _do_ have 
individual existence. Redness is embodied in the different words that 
mean 'red' in different languages, by the cells of the retina that 
enable us to perceive things as 'red', etc. You could say that before 
a book can be red, 'redness' has to exist by itself.

-*-*-*-*-*-
 Morendil

