csg419@wing.rug.nl writes:
>
>======================================================================
>			ASSIGNMENT CFJ 835
>======================================================================
>Judge:		Dave Bowen
>Judgement:	FALSE
>======================================================================
>Full Statement:
>
>Rule 1023 shall be interpreted, such that for each action which a
>Player is obliged to perform, but fails to perform, within the time
>required by this Rule is a separate and distinct Crime, and
>furthermore each action performed by a Player in an order which is
>inconsistent with the requirements of this Rule is itself a Crime
>separate and distinct from each other such action, and from any Crime
>for failure to meet the time requirement.
>======================================================================
>Decision & Reasoning Judge:
>Decision: FALSE
>
>Reasoning: My interpretation of this rule is that a crime is committed for
>           each out-of-order action.  Thus, using the Caller's example an
>           order of D2, D0, D1 would be two crimes, not the one crime the
>           Caller claims, since both D0 and D1 are required to precede D2.
>           Similarly, an order of D2, D1, D0 would be three crimes, not the
>           two Caller claims; the two crimes for D2 preceding D0 and D1 plus
>           one for D1 preceding D0.
>
>======================================================================

This Judgement seems plausible on the face of it - until one considers
the timing of the allegedly Criminal acts.

Consider the ordering D2, D0, D1. Kelly argued that this is one Crime,
since only one action is out of sequence. Judge Bowen wants to say
that it's two Crimes, since both D0 and D1 ought to precede D2. This
makes it appear as if Kelly and Bowen hold equally good views. But
the appearance is deceptive. Kelly's view has a great advantage and
Bowen's a correspondingly great disadvantage: in Kelly's view, the
single Crime which is committed is committed *when D2 is performed*.
This is a great advantage of Kelly's view since it maintains the
intuitively plausible view that the time a Crime is committed is the
time that the Criminal act is performed. On Bowen's view, the Crimes
are committed when D0 and D1 are performed. Of course, Bowen will say
that it is the performance of D0 and D1 which are Criminal, and so it
is natural to tie the timing of the Crime to the timing of these acts.

But I deny that it is the performance of D0 and D1 in themselves that
constitutes the Crime. Clearly, it is the performance of D2 out of turn
which is the problem. If the required ordering is D0, D1, D2, then
we can already tell, once D2 has been performed, that a Crime has
been committed. Why then must we wait, as Bowen would have us do,
for D0 and D1 to be performed to find out when the crime is committed?
What if D0 and D1, for whatever reason, are *never* performed? This
would leave us with the absurd situation of knowing that a Crime
has been committed without being able to say - even roughly! - when
it occurred.

Since there absurdities lurking in Bowen's Judgement, I hereby Appeal
the Judgement of CFJ 835.

