Kelly writes:
>i'm sorry, but i cannot accept Dave's interpretation of R.1023.  in
>fact, his argument is contradictory: he claims that there are two
>"out-of-order" actions taken in the order "D2, D0, D1", but the only
>action performed out of order is D2.

I'll let Kelly provide eir definition for out-of-order.  Mine is simple.  If
there are n actions in the chain D_1, D_2, ..., D_n with D_1 required to be
performed first, D_2 second, etc., then an out-of-order action occurs for
i and j in 1..n where i < j and D_i happens after D_j.  Thus in the ordering
D2, D0, D1, D2 is out-of-order with respect to both D0 and D1 and under my
definition this constitutes two crimes.

David Bowen

