It doesn't make sense to me to make all these bounded spaces thousands of
cimons in extent.  If you're going to actually use all this space, the
Cartographer's (Cartographor's?) job will be absolute hell.  On the other
hand, if you don't use all the space (or at least a significant fraction
of it), what's the point of all these interesting geometries?  Close up,
they'll either look polar or rectangular, and will be essentially
indistinguishable from infinite spaces.

How many Agora entities will you be interested in keeping track of the
location of?  Now, why would you want millions of times that number of
locations?

If you use the whole space, objects will be spread many cimons apart.
This makes simons look like very fine grades of distance.  So effectively
you've given the positions of objects with great precision.  To what
purpose?  I think that more than anything else, this would lead to an
excessive reliance on complex distance formulas and decreased interest.
Thus, I think the gradations of location should remain coarse.  

Even a go board, at 19x19, is fairly spacious for 10-20 Players.  19
players could each own 19 locations - you could develop alot in 19
locations.  Why make it thousands?  *I* wouldn't be interested in
managing thousands of locations individually.  Would you play go on a
100x100 board?  1000x1000?  Sure, this probably won't turn into anything
like go, but I expect the dynamics to be similarly complex.  Would you
expect anything less from Agora?

-Jesse

