On Wed, 29 Nov 1995, Steven A Swiniarski wrote:

> PROTO: Agoraspace v2.2

> Let the following Rule be created (Agoraspace):

>            v2.2--Changed this Origin to "Locus," because upon reflection
>            Origin should refer to the {0,0} Coordinates on the surface
>            we use.  Therefore I've moved the clause about default
>            location (the Locus is a reference point.)}

I think it sounds ugly ("locust"?) , and I don't think I like this 
"improvement". If you must, adjust so the Origin is in the surface.

> Let the following rule be created (Coordinates in Agoraspace):
> 
>      Locus.  When the Rules refer to an X, Y, or Z axis, they shall be
>      the first three axes of this coordinate system.  The AB planes are
>      those planes parallel to the plane containing the A and B axes,
>      including that plane, where A and B are two different axes from
>      three axes X, Y, or Z.  A specific AB plane can be specified by a

"the three axes".

>      coordinate on the excluded axis.

I didn't think it was customary to allow "XY plane" to refer to a plane
not containing the Origin. 

I feel that this formuletion may restrict us too much to a 3D space.

> Let the following Rule be created (Agora is a non-Euclidean Surface):

>      Linear distances within this surface is calculated differently from 
>      the (Euclidean) distances in Agoraspace outside the surface.  The 
>      Linear distance between the two locations <X,Y> and <A,B> is
>      |X - Y| + |Y - A|. Where X and A are the Latitudes smallest in

Where did the B go?

Assume that the longitude wraps around at 360. Should the distance between
two points (say, at X=359, A=1, Y=B=100) close to each side of the "date
line" _really_ be almost 360? 

You may have meant to imply to use X=-1, but you have not provided for 
this in your later definitions of specific surfaces.

>      absolute magnitude that apply to the locations in question, and Y & 
>      B are the Longitudes smallest in absolute magnitude that apply to 
>      the locations in question.

Ouch. Manhattan metric does _not_ work with polar coordinates; You can
sometimes get from one point to another faster by going via the Origin
than by following the latitude line, which means the distance should be
along the first road, not the last one (the triangle inequality, which
every metric must fulfil.) What is the distance to the Origin under this
scheme, anyhow? 

Unless you are on a rectangle, Euclidian distance is nicer.

BTW, it occurs to me that the Cartographor should report latitude & 
longitude rather than coordinates.

>           unchanged.  I'd esp. like comment from the math people as to
>           if this'll work like I expect.}

I don't like it.

> Option #1-------------------------------------------------------------
> Let the following rule be created (The Agoradisk):

>      Locations within the Agoradisk can be specified by at least one
>      pair of coordinates.  The first coordinate is the location's
>      longitude, which is 2 pi cimons multiplied by its angle. Its angle
>      being measured clockwise around the disk's circumference, with

"is measured". That sentence no verb.

What do you measure the angle as? Degrees? Radians? (None of which are 
nice when multiplied with 2 pi cimons.)

>      angle 0 on the positive X axis. The second coordinate is the
>      location's latitude, which is the location's radial (Euclidean)
>      distance from the Origin.
> 
> {Comment: This is the simplest bounded space to talk about, a circle
>           floating in empty space.
> 
>           v2.1--I borrowed kelly's wording, to an extent.  I still want
>           the 2d surface floating within an existing Nd space.  I also
>           think if we define the place, we should also define a
>           coordinate system to go with it.  Changed the name of the
>           thing to Agoradisk per _many_ requests.  Changed the surface
>           references to polar coords.
> 
>           v2.2--I hope the coordinates still make sense.  They're still
>           essentially polar, but I redefined longitude to be measured in
>           cimons. (Resulting in the weird situation where, within the
>           disk itself, all the latitudinal circles are the same
>           circumference, and all the radial lines are parallel.)}

It's a cylinder internally then, except for the Origin, where all h**l 
breaks loose.

Actually, a Manhattan metric might work, provided a circumference is no 
longer than two diameters. (Bye bye, pi, we'll never miss you :-)

> Option #2--------------------------------------------------------------
> Let the following rule be created (The Agorasphere):

>      All locations upon the Agorasphere can be specified by at least one 
>      pair of coordinates. The first coordinate is the location's 
>      longitude, which is 2 pi cimons multiplied by its angle.  Its angle
>      is measured clockwise around the Equator with angle 0 on the 
>      positive X axis.  The second coordinate is the location's latitude, 
>      which is 2 pi cimons multiplied by its angle.  Its angle is 
>      measured clockwise from the North Pole to the South Pole.

As above, the angles are not clearly defined; and here too, watch out for 
distances via the Poles.

>           v2.2--re:Orejan, the Equator doesn't get angle 0.  And I do
>           think this definition is self-contained.

No, it is not. Are the angles both centered at the Locus? One of them
shouldn't be.

> Option #3--------------------------------------------------------------
> Let the following rule be created (The Agorus):

>      All locations upon the Agorasphere can be specified by at least one 
>      pair of coordinates. The first coordinate is the location's 
>      longitude, which is 2 pi cimons multiplied by its angle.  Its angle
>      is measured clockwise around the Equators, with angle 0 on the 
>      positive X axis. The second coordinate is the location's latitude,
>      which is pi cimons multiplied by its angle.  Its angle is 
>      measured around Agorus' circular cross-section starting from the 
>      North Parallel, towards the Outer Equator.

As above, the units of the angles are not defined. Otherwise, the 
Manhattan Metric seems to work for a torus.

For the others, I can't stand it.

