> 
> PROTO: Agoraspace v2.2
> 
> Let the following Rule be created (Agoraspace):
> [9-line rule]
> 
> Let the following rule be created (Coordinates in Agoraspace):
> [10-line rule]
> 
> Let the following Rule be created (Units of Measure):
>      The official unit of linear measure within Agoraspace is the cimon.  
>      All measurements of distance in Agoraspace shall be made in cimon.  
>      SI prefixes can be used to specify larger or smaller distances 
>      without ambiguity.  (1 kilocimon = 1000 cimons = 1,000,000 
>      milicimons.)  All Entities within Agoraspace extend zero cimons in
>      all dimensions unless explicitly defined otherwise in the Rules.
> 
>      The official unit of angular measure within Agoraspace is the 
>      agorad. Agorads divide a circumference into one-thousandths.
>      (1 agorad = 0.36 degrees.)

Ok, here I have a question: Why not 6 Agorads per circumference?  Before
everyone jumps on my case, this isn't completely arbitrary.  In RL,
there are 2*pi ~= 6.28 radians per circumference.  This is so that in a
circle of radius 1, an arc of 1 radian is exactly the same length as the
radius.  Well, 6 is _close_, and has the advantage of being an
integer... and we aren't really striving for a strictly Real system.
(*groan*) (Or even for the intelligibility of the Indiana State Code! :)
Alternatively, some multiple of this, such as 600 or 6000.

> Let the following Rule be created (The Cartographor):
> [12-line rule]
> 
> Let the following Rule be created (The Rules Bind Agoraspace):
> [11-line rule]
> 
> Let the following Rule be created (Agora is a non-Euclidean Surface):
> 
>      All Entities in Agoraspace exist within a surface of two 
>      dimensions, as defined in other Rules.  Such a surface must also 
>      have an associated coordinate system which defines the Longitude 
>      and Latitude of every location within the surface.  The Origin is a 
>      special location within the surface, where the Longitude and 
>      Latitude are both equal to zero.
> 
>      Linear distances within this surface is calculated differently from 
>      the (Euclidean) distances in Agoraspace outside the surface.  The 
>      Linear distance between the two locations <X,Y> and <A,B> is
>      |X - Y| + |Y - A|. Where X and A are the Latitudes smallest in

I think you mean X-A and Y-B, but I'm not sure.

>      absolute magnitude that apply to the locations in question, and Y & 
>      B are the Longitudes smallest in absolute magnitude that apply to 
>      the locations in question.
> 
>      In the absence of a Rule defining this surface, this surface shall 
>      be the XY plane where Z = 0, X shall be the Latitude, Y shall be 
>      the Longitude and the Origin shall be at the Locus.

Why do you need this?  Who says it has to be in any plane at all?  It's
_its own manifold_, it has no relation to X, Y, or Z planes as we know
them.

> Option #1-------------------------------------------------------------
> Let the following rule be created (The Agoradisk):
> 
>      The Agoradisk is a two dimensional disk centered on the Locus.  It 
>      lies on the XY plane Z = 0.  Its radius is one kilocimon.  Entities 
>      within Agoraspace are constrained to exist only within the 
>      locations contained within the Agoradisk.

Axe the second sentence...

>      The Origin is at the same location as the Locus.
> 
>      Locations within the Agoradisk can be specified by at least one
>      pair of coordinates.  The first coordinate is the location's
>      longitude, which is 2 pi cimons multiplied by its angle. Its angle
>      being measured clockwise around the disk's circumference, with
>      angle 0 on the positive X axis. The second coordinate is the
>      location's latitude, which is the location's radial (Euclidean)
>      distance from the Origin.

Try:
      Locations within the Agoradisk can be specified by exactly one
      pair of coordinates.  The reference on the Agoradisk is a single
      line beginning at the origin, and extending to infinity.  The
      first coordinate is the location's longitude, which is the
      location's distance from the Origin (measured in cimons).  The
      second coordinate is the location's latitude, which is the angle
      between the reference and a line from the location to the Origin,
      measured clockwise from the reference, in agorads.  The range of
      values for the first coordinate is from 0 to infinity, and the 
      range for the second is [0, 1000); 0 is a legal value, 1000 is not.

Unfortunately, it is slightly longer, but has a couple of advantages: it
is not bound to any type of space, and it has a unique coordinate
system.  Also, the coordinates are now in the correct order, and the
"latitude" and "longitude" are properly named. 

>           v2.2--I hope the coordinates still make sense.  They're still
>           essentially polar, but I redefined longitude to be measured in
>           cimons. (Resulting in the weird situation where, within the
>           disk itself, all the latitudinal circles are the same
>           circumference, and all the radial lines are parallel.)}

Well, this isn't really a Euclidean disk--it's more like a Euclidean
cylinder, except that one end of the cylinder is collapsed to a single
point.  IOW, it has no exact Euclidean equivalent, but that's not a
problem.

> Option #2--------------------------------------------------------------
> Let the following rule be created (The Agorasphere):
> 
>      The Agorasphere is the surface of a three dimensional sphere
>      centered on the Locus.  The Agorasphere intersects the X, Y and Z
>      axes, and has a radius of one kilocimon. Entities within Agoraspace
>      are constrained to exist only within the locations contained within
>      the Agorasphere.

Axe the second sentence.

>      The circle where the XY plane Z = 0 intersects the Agorasphere is 
>      the Equator.  The location where the positive Z axis intersects the
>      Agorasphere is the North Pole. The location where the negative
>      Z axis intersects the Agorasphere is the South Pole.

"The references of the Agorasphere are the North Pole and the South
Pole, which are diametrically opposed points; the G-line, which connects
the Poles, and the Equator, the great circle which perpendicularly
bisects the G-line."

(G-line is so named because of the RL Greenwich line.)

>      The Origin is at the same location as the North Pole.
> 
>      All locations upon the Agorasphere can be specified by at least one 
>      pair of coordinates. The first coordinate is the location's 
>      longitude, which is 2 pi cimons multiplied by its angle.  Its angle
>      is measured clockwise around the Equator with angle 0 on the 
>      positive X axis.  The second coordinate is the location's latitude, 
>      which is 2 pi cimons multiplied by its angle.  Its angle is 
>      measured clockwise from the North Pole to the South Pole.

"All locations upon the Agorasphere can be specified by exactly one pair
of coordinates.  The first is the latitude, which is measured by
calculating a plane parallel to the Equator, and passing through the
location.  The latitude is the angular measure along the G-line
(starting with 0 at the North Pole) where the plane intersects the
G-line.  The second is longitude, which is measured by calculating the
plane which intersects both poles and the location.  The longitude is
the angular measure along the equator (measured clockwise with 0 at the
G-line) where the plane intersects the Equator.  The range of values for
latitude is [0, 500), and the range for longitude is [0, 1000)."

>           v2.2--re:Orejan, the Equator doesn't get angle 0.  And I do
>           think this definition is self-contained.
>           In the surface this would now appear more like a weirdly
>           distorted cylinder than a sphere, (the Longitudinal
>           lines are parallels now.)  BTW, you can forget all prior
>           comments re:area. disk = 2 pi million sq. cimons
>                           sphere = 39.5 million sq. cimons

Somewhat similar to #1, this is a little like a cylinder except _both_
ends are single points.  Non-Euclidean, but no biggie.

> Option #3--------------------------------------------------------------
> Let the following rule be created (The Agorus):
> 
>      The Agorus is the surface of a three dimensional torus centered on 
>      the Locus and the Z axis.  The Agorus intersects the XY plane, has 
>      a major radius of one kilocimon, and a minor radius of one-half 
>      kilocimon.  (The Agorus' surface is that generated by rotating a 
>      base circle completely around the Z axis.  This base circle lies in 
>      the XZ plane, is one-half kilocimon in radius, and is centered on 
>      the point upon the X axis one kilocimon away from the Locus in the 
>      positive X direction.) Entities within Agoraspace are constrained 
>      to exist only within the locations contained within the Agorus, or 
>      the Locus.

First of all, it is a 2D torus you describe.  Only the embedding in
Euclidean space is 3D.  (Actually, come to think of it, the same is true
for #1 and #2.)  Get rid of all the embedding language, and just put
"The Agorus is the surface of a 2D torus centered on the Locus.
Entities within....".  And I believe you mean "Origin", not "Locus", in
the last sentence?

>      The circles where the XY plane Z = 0 intersects the Agorus are 
>      known as the Equators.  The smaller is the Inner Equator (radius = 
>      one-half kilocimon.)  The larger is the Outer Equator (radius = one 
>      and one-half kilocimon.)  The circle on Agorus where Z = +0.5 
>      kilocimons is the North Parallel.  The circle on Agorus where Z = -
>      0.5 kilocimons is the South Parallel.

This is tricky stuff to implement in a toroidal manifold (i.e. "top" and
"bottom" have no meaning in a torus).  But I really don't think it's all
needed?  "The references for the Agorus are two perpendicular lines, the
Major Equator and the Minor Equator."  Actually, if you like, you could
even call them X and Y axes.  As for the word "line", well, I don't
think that's the right term, but I don't know the right one.  Kelly
probably does, or Orjan.  Oh, and add "The Equators are orientable, and
have a positive and a negative direction."

>      The Origin is at the location where the XZ plane Y = 0 intersects 
>      the North Parallel.

The Origin is at the intersection of the Equators.

>      All locations upon the Agorasphere can be specified by at least one 
>      pair of coordinates. The first coordinate is the location's 
>      longitude, which is 2 pi cimons multiplied by its angle.  Its angle
>      is measured clockwise around the Equators, with angle 0 on the 
>      positive X axis. The second coordinate is the location's latitude,
>      which is pi cimons multiplied by its angle.  Its angle is 
>      measured around Agorus' circular cross-section starting from the 
>      North Parallel, towards the Outer Equator.

"All locations upon the Agor*us* can be specified by exactly one pair of
coordinates.  The first coordinate is the location's latitude, which is
the distance of the location from the Minor Equator, in the positive
direction of the Major Equator.  The second is the location's longitude,
which is the distance of the location from the Major Equator, in the
positive direction of the Minor Equator.  Each is measured in cimons,
and the range of values for each is [0, 1000)."

Actually, this is by far the simplest of the proposed designs.  If you
eliminate the "Equator" and "longitude" and "latitude" stuff (which I
only wrote in to parallel the other two options), it would be even
simpler.  Also, this one has a nice, even area: 1 square kilocimon, or 1
million square cimons.

>           v2.2-- Fixed the plane of longitude measurement.  This is
>           essentially combining a 2d representation of kelly's
>           preference (at least I hope I did it) w/ my preference for
>           having a surface floating in a larger space.  This is the
>           basic asteroid grid (though narrower than it is long.)
>           area now = 19.7 million sq. cimons (apparently my equalization
>           of circles is much less a distortion of a torus-- it averages
>           out-- than it is of a sphere.)}

Incidentally, if you are really keen on the idea, we can always embed
this later, once you come up with something to relate it to.

Vanyel

