Note: I've now resubcribed to n-d, although I'll probably come
to regret it... :)

I guess what I was really trying to say in my earlier post
is that the distance function should describe a surface
which is at least *topologically* equivalent to what we
claim the surface actually is.  Swann's distance function works
fine for a plane with orthoganal axes, but not for a disk (at least
with longitude and latitude as he defines it) or for a sphere or
torus.  Using Swann's distance function, the "disk" has discontinuities
at the origin and along the Greenwich Meridian; the "sphere" has
discontinuities at both poles and along the Greenwich Meridian,
and the "torus" has discontinuities along the equator and
Greenwich Meridian.

To me it seems like it is doing things backwards to define the
distance function first and then choose which surface we want;
it makes more sense to me to choose first which sort of surface
we want and how to define latitude and longitude, and only then
to choose an appropriate distance function.

Chuck

