Steven A Swiniarski writes:
> 
> PROTO: Agoraspace v3.0
> 
> Note: Much as I like embedding Agoraspace, I have dismissed the idea for
> the time being, since too many players objected to it.  [...]

And a non-player.  :)  (I'll probably be joining come January, though.)

> Let the following Rule be created (Units of Measure):
> 
>      The official unit of linear measure within Agoraspace is the cimon.  
>      All measurements of distance in Agoraspace shall be made in cimon.  
>      SI prefixes can be used to specify larger or smaller distances 
>      without ambiguity.  (1 kilocimon = 1000 cimons = 1,000,000 
>      millicimons.)  All Entities within Agoraspace extend zero cimons in
>      all dimensions unless explicitly defined otherwise in the Rules.
> 
>      The SI abbreviation of cimon is "Ci."
> 
>      The official unit of angular measure within Agoraspace is the 
>      agorad. Agorads divide a circumference into unity.
>      (1 agorad = 360 degrees.)

Hah!  :)  But why not just call it a Cylce?  (Abbreviation Cy?)

BTW, why say you're using SI units?  These units are unique to Agora, and
Agora apparently does not use other SI units, except possibly the second.

> Let the following Rule be created (The Rules Bind Agoraspace):
> 
>      All Entities in Agoraspace shall only exist at those locations, 
>      or sets of locations, wherein the Rules expressly give permission 
>      for those Entities to exist.  Within such boundaries, all Entities 
>      which are permitted to exist at a location may all coexist at 
>      that location without limit.

Hmm.  I wonder if it might not be better to specify some subset of
Entities which exist at locations in Agoraspace.  Call them Physical
Entities.  Only those Entities specified by the Rules to be Physical
Entities are such, and occupy locations in Agoraspace.  I suggest this
because there is such ongoing discussion about what are Entities.  (If
a player's On Hold status is an Entity, does it have a location?  Why?
Could I steal it?  :] )

> Let the following Rule be created (Agoraspace is non-Euclidean):
> 
>      All Entities in Agoraspace exist within a surface of two 
>      dimensions, as defined in other Rules.  Such a surface must also 
>      have an associated coordinate system which defines the Longitude 
>      and Latitude of every location within the surface.  The Origin is a 
>      special location within the surface, where the Longitude and 
>      Latitude are both equal to zero.
> 
>      When the Rules refer to the coordinates of a location, they refer
>      to a paired Longitude and Latitude referring to that location.
> 
>      Linear distances in Agoraspace between the two locations
>      (X,Y) and (A,B) is |X - A| + |Y - B|. Where X and A are the
>      Longitudes smallest in absolute magnitude that apply to the
>      locations in question, and Y & B are the Latitudes smallest in
>      absolute magnitude that apply to the locations in question.

Since you went to the effort above to define units, you should use them
here.  There's no sense defining a unit of distance if it never appears in
a distance formula!

I don't see how this connects with the later 'Options for the "Surface" of
Agora'.  Is it a separate option?

I still think that distances should be derived, rather than legislated.
For instance, suppose in a 1-dimensional toroidal space of length 100Ci,
I am at (95) and have 10 Movement Units to spend during the week, meaning
I can travel a distance of up to 10Ci.  If distance is _defined_ to be
|X-A|, then I can't make use of the toroidal wrap-around to go to (5),
because that would be (by definition) a distance of |5-95| = 90.  You
could, of course, define the mathematics in such a way that this problem
is eliminated.  But what happens when a new space is legislated that
connects to this one, such as a 10Ci shortcut loop between (25) and (75)?
Formulas will get very ugly very fast.  So just define some kind of step
size (surely, space will be quantized) and define the distance as the
smallest number of steps from one location to another.  Then you don't
have to rework complex distance legislation every time the space gets
changed.

> ======================================================================
> 
> Three Options for the "Surface" of Agora.

> Option #1-------------------------------------------------------------
> Let the following rule be created (The Agoradisk):

> {Comment: 
> 
>           v3.0--Thanks to Vanyel for some of the language.  I _hope_ my
>           definition here doesn't badly interact with my redefinition of
>           distance (again I await comment from the math people.) re:
>           Oerjan-- I'll take your comments about that as a vote in favor
>           of Agorus :)  Look ma, no embedding, and no Cartesian
>           coordinates. (Would people prefer the Equator to be the
>           perimeter?.)  Also note:  The range of coordinates are now
>           only 10 cimons.}

But what are the subdivisions?  I notice you still have millicimons
defined...

> Option #2--------------------------------------------------------------
> Let the following rule be created (The Agorasphere):

> {Comment: 
>           v3.0-- Somehow I managed w/o refrence to a third dimention.  I
>           think the definition of Lattitude is consistent.}

It certainly _felt_ like a 3-dimensional description to me.  It could
just be me.

I think I would have tried just to describe the coordinates and their
properties.  I suppose it makes a difference whether you're trying to
closely model real distances on real spherical surfaces, etc.

> Option #3--------------------------------------------------------------
> Let the following rule be created (The Agorus):
> 
>      Agoraspace is a toroidal surface which contains, and is fixed in 
>      reference to, the Origin.  Its major circumference is twenty 
>      cimons, and its minor circumference is ten cimons. There is a fixed 
>      line parallel to the major circumference and containing the Origin.  
>      This line is the Equator.  There is a fixed line, parallel to the 
>      minor circumference and perpendicular to the Equator, also 
>      containing the Origin.  This line is the Greenwich Meridian.
>
>      Both lines completely encircle Agoraspace along their 
>      circumference, and have a fixed direction associated with them.
>      The direction of the Equator is East. (Directions parallel and
>      opposed are West.)  The direction of the Greenwich Meridian is
>      North. (Directions parallel and opposed are South.)
> 
>      Locations on the Greenwich Meridian have Longitude zero, the 
>      Longitude of any other location is its distance East, in cimons, 
>      from the Greenwich Meridian.
> 
>      Locations on the Equator have Latitude zero, the Latitude of any 
>      other location is its distance North, in cimons, from the Equator.
> 
>      This surface, as a whole, is the Agorus.
> 
> {Comment: 
>           v3.0-- Here it is, the surface of popular demand.  Now with a
>           rule about 100 words shorter.  Also absent are any references
>           to angular measurement.  It's still essentially the same thing
>           as in v2.2, though with the parallels renamed.  Ok, I admit
>           it, it's simpler :)}

It is, but the wording seems quite complex to me.  Again, I would start
with the coordinates (latitude and longitude).  Then, I'd specify their
toroidal properties, and define the Equator and Greenwich Meridian from
them only if I felt really energetic.  (Eg, the GM is the set of locations
for which Longitude = 0.)  But such complexities seem quite unnecessary.

-Jesse

