Don Blaheta was heard to say:
> 
> > > > PROTO-PROPOSAL
> > > > Petitions
> > > 
> > > I thought we already had Referenda for things like this. No need to 
> > > invent another type of Entity.
> > 
> > 1) Petitions only relate to Players, not Voting Entities. 2) Petitions
> > have no Voting Period and thus may be faster, or slower, depending on
> > support for the Petition. 3) Signatures to a Petition may be retracted.
> > 4) No formal Voting process is needed for Petitions. 5) Petitions need
> > not be secret; in fact, they are subject to public perusal; this may or
> > may not be the intended result; we just haven't thought about it. 
> > 6) Petitions are not subject to Quorum Rules. 
> 
> All of these things, though specified in the Referendum Rule, are
> specifically called _defaults_.  If you really need a petition, you can
> always specify the non-defaults where needed, or at the very least make
> them a special case of Referenda, much like Elections are.

Creating a new class is actually easier than trying to make them fit
into the current Referenda Rules. The Referenda Rules add a lot of
excess baggage which would have to be explicitly trimmed in the Petition
Rules; the things remaining are fewer than the things which would be
removed from the default Refrenda Rules. It doesn't make sense to
specify X things to change than to specify one third of X things which
will actually be true. 

Besides, although it may or may not happen, and although we are not
going to push for it, encourage it, or really attempt to cause it to
happen in any way, we still wouldn't be surprised to see Referenda
phased out with the existance of Petitions and self-Promoted and
Assessed Proposals. Their usefulness in that environment would seem to
be diminished. 


Enjoy!

