Zefram writes:
>
> Okay, so where is the Agoraverse within the bounds of Agoraspace?
> 
> -zefram

I'd like to mention again the idea of giving locations only to those
entities specified by the rules to the Physical Entities.  This would
eliminate such quandries, which could conceivably cause unanticipated
problems somewhere down the road.

I would also suggest limiting the positions of entities in a way less
dependent upon the specification of any particular subspace of the
Agoraverse.  Come to think of it, why even define the Agoraverse at all?
Instead, what about something like this:

(Location and Agoraspace)

	Agoraspace consists of all Locations defined by the Rules.

	No Location exists which is not defined by the Rules to be a
	Location.  All Locations defined by the Rules are distinct,
	except as specified otherwise by the Rules.

	There is a Location called the Origin.

{ Note:	This makes it very easy to add new sections to Agoraspace.
	Just define new Locations, and how they connect to (see below)
	or overlap with the previously-defined Locations.  No going
	back to modify old rules necessary. }

(Physical Entities and Position)

	Only those Entities specified by the Rules to be Physical
	Entities are Physical Entities.

	Every Physical Entity, and nothing which is not a Physical
	Entity, exists at a Location in Agoraspace.  This Location is
	the Position of the Physical Entity.  (Things which are not
	Physical Entities may still exist in the abstract, but do not
	have a Position in Agoraspace.)

	Any Physical Entity whose Position is not otherwise determined,
	explicitly or implicitly by the Rules, exists at the Origin.

	The Position of a Physical Entity may only change as specified
	by the Rules.

	[List some Physical Entities here: Players, Marks, The Nomic
	Potato, etc.]

{ Note:	No worries about unexpected Entities implicitly being located at
	the Origin, since only specified PEs exist in space.  These will
	be easier to keep track of and take into account in legislation
	about Agoraspace. }

(Adjacency, Path, and Distance: the Quantization of Space)

	Locations are only Adjacent if they are specified the the Rules
	to be Adjacent.  If a Location X is Adjacent to a Location Y,
	then Y is Adjacent to X, and X and Y are Adjacent.  (This
	defines two uses of "Adjacent".)

	A Path is a sequence of Locations, each of which is adjacent to
	the next, if any.  (There is, of course, no location next after
	the last in the sequence.)  A Path from A to B is a Path which
	has as A as its first element, and B as its final element.  The
	Length of a Path (also called the Distance along a Path) is the
	number of elements in the Path's sequence, minus 1.

	The Distance between two Locations A and B (also called the
	Distance from A to B) is defined to be the Length of the shortest
	Path from A to B.

{ Note:	I've taken here an explicitly lattice-like approach to space
	and its quantization.  All distances are integers, and space is
	not infinitely sub-dividable.  I rather like this approach
	because (1) it produces a simple space, with simple measure and
	easily described paths, (2) it permits rather simple descriptions
	of sub-spaces (see below), (3) you never again have to give a
	definition of distances between points, (4) it is possible to
	directly discuss connections between points, who owns them, and
	all kinds of other fun possibilities, and (5) there's no mucking
	around with unimportant small fractions of unit distance. }

(Agorus)

	The Agorus is a subspace of Agoraspace consisting of certain
	Locations which can be uniquely specified by T(x,y), where x
	and y are integer co-ordinates of the Location.  For any
	integers x and y, T(x,y) is a location with the following
	properties:

		T(x,y) is identical to both T(x+40,y) and T(x,y+20);
		T(x,y) is adjacent to both T(x+1,y) and T(x,y+1).

	T(0,0) is identical to the Origin.

{ Note:	Wasn't that simple? :) }

-Jesse

