Kelly Martin writes:
>
>"Charles" == Charles E Carroll <ccarroll@students.wisc.edu> writes:
>
>Charles> Steve's Event proto specifies that changing any property
>Charles> referred to in the Rules--even if it's not what we would
>Charles> think of as a Game Entity-- is an Event.  Does this mean if
>Charles> my age is referred to in the Rules, I'm not allowed to have a
>Charles> birthday without explicit permission of the Rules?
>
>age being a derived property, i don't think there is a problem as long
>as the Rules permit time to pass (and with this version of 1011 i am
>proposing, we might well have to legislate this).

I don't want to have to do this. I would feel as ridiculous legislating
for the passage of time as I would legislating for the value of pi -
even if the legislation specified the correct value! (Or the first
thousand digits of the decimal expansion of it, or even just an
algorithm for computing it.)

No, despite the perplexities it introduces, I think we have to admit that
some events can occur despite not being required to occur by the Rules.
I suppose an example would be: the beginning of each new Nomic Week.

Related question: are all the events directly caused by moves are
required to occur by the Rules? Even though the move itself might not
be required by the Rules? Eg: the move of voluntarily making a Marks
transfer is permitted but not required, but the event of the Marks
moving from one Treasury to another is required by the Rules. But
now: what about the move of changing one's email address? This causes
the event of one's email address changing.  Is that event required to
occur? If so, what Rule requires it?

