On Mon, 4 Dec 1995, Steve Gardner wrote:

> treat for convenience somewhat like non-retractable moves. The way to
> put these aside is to consider what things would be like under
> conditions of perfect knowledge, in which all errors are immediately
> detected. Under those conditions, presumably all retractable errors
> would be immediately retracted. What then?

Retracted, or never happen at all.

> The list above seems to me to contain a couple of different kinds
> of things. I'd put tomorrow's weather, and the speed of light, along
> with things like the value of pi and the passage of time, into one
> basket. Into that basket go all of the things that it makes no
> conceptual sense for us to legislate about. Right now, I can do
> nothing more than have a rough stab at what they all have in
> common, but here it is (for what it's worth): I'd say that they're
> all brute facts with which we have to live, beyond the control of
> any Player. Or any person, for that matter.

I just want to mention that a Norwegian county a couple years ago made an
ordinance to have nice summer weather. I believe this ordinance was obeyed.

