Kelly sez:

> given this degree of arbitrariness, the likelihood of success a caller
> has on a CFJ is largely dependent on who is selected as Judge, and
> almost not at all on the merits of the claim.  this situation, imo, is
> intolerable.

Quite right. I'm sure that the Rules for Barring Players from Judging 
a CFJ have a lot to do with that, too... Influencing the selection of 
the Judge in this way has obviously been a profitable tactic in past
CFJs.

To date, here are the specific aspects of our hypothetical Code of 
Evidence, to my recollection, that have been brought up :

* timing of Moves
(what determines when a Move was made and when the resulting Event 
takes place ? A "Date:" header, and if so, which one ? What about my 
Kudo transfers that were sent last week and got to the lists only 
yesterday ?)

* burden of proof
(If an Officer claims not to have received a Move a Player claims to 
have sent, or the reverse, who has to present proof ? What 
constitutes proof ?)

* formalism of arguments
(Many Judgements have been appealed on the grounds of arguments being
'absurd', sometimes justifiably... Do we need to have a 'proper form' 
for presenting arguments & reasonings ?)

Also, there is the more general problem of how we use this Code. Is 
there a Rule that makes Judgements illegal if they don't conform ? 
Can that Rule result in CFJs itself ? Who decides whether a Judgement 
conforms to the Code ?
---**---
Morendil

