   Thu, 07 Dec 95 15:37:14 EST
Date: Thu, 7 Dec 95 15:37:14 EST
From: "David M. Chess" <chess@watson.ibm.com>
To: nomic-discussion@teleport.com
Subject: Proposal 2045 and accidental TIAs
Sender: owner-nomic-discussion@teleport.com
Precedence: bulk
Reply-To: nomic-discussion@teleport.com
Status: RO

I greatly admire the underlying intent of 2045, but as a TIA
violator myself I have a concern.

>     The designations of the Distributor notwithstanding, sending a
>     message via any medium or combination of media such that every
>     Active Player receives it is equivalent to sending a message to
>     the Public Forum.

I expect this was all gone over while I was On Hold, but mightn't
this accidentally expand the scope of TIA considerably?  I mean,
if all Agorans happened to be subscribed to MUFFINS-L, but the
Distributor didn't happen to notice this and explicitly declare
MUFFINS-L a non-PF, then any posting to MUFFINS-L would be "equivalent
to sending a message to the Public Forum", and therefore presumably
subject to TIA?  Which seems like an undesirable result?

Is there any particular reason to avoid labeling requirements?
I think it might more directly accomplish the goal if posting
to the PF were declared to be accomplished by either of:

  - Posting to the Distributor-defined PF, or
  - Sending a message in such a way that it reaches all
    Players, *and* clearly labelling the message as being
    a posting to the Agora Public Forum.

This would avoid accidental PF-postings, while still avoiding
insane distributors...

| favor |

