Kelly Martin was heard to say:
> 
> that is part of the argument i make, yes.  the other applies
> specifically only to Marks and Points, and regards their divisibility.
> if you transfer 1 Mark to me, i can turn around and divvy that Mark up
> into 100 pieces and strew those pieces about seemingly at random.  i
> don't think something that i can take and chop up into little pieces
> and then throw around like confetti to be recombined with other pieces
> of confetti to make another thing indistinguishable from the first to
> have "individual existence".  indivisibility is generally considered a
> requirement to identity, and Marks (and Points) are clearly divisible.
> 
> one could argue that centimarks are indivisible, and thus each
> centimark has "identity", but the Rules never speak at all about
> centimarks, by that name or any other.

A piece of paper is an Entity, right? It is obviously a piece of paper,
and has an individual existance. It's right here. Now I tear the piece
of paper in half. Wow. Now there are two pieces of paper. Both would be
Entities, right? Now let's say I tape those pieces of paper back
togther, so it's one piece of paper again. It's still an Entity. Why
wouldn't it be? 

How is this different than the divisibility of Marks or Points? 


