Status: RO

Steven A Swiniarski writes:
>PROTO:Vote of Confidence

OK, I've dug this up and had a closer look at it. I think the idea is
good, but I think the proto still needs some fine tuning. Some of the
language used is a bit loose, inaccurate or awkward.

>
>Let the following Rule be created (Vote of Confidence Directive.):
>
>    "There is a Directive known as a Vote of Confidence (VOC).  A
>     Proposal containing a VOC Directive must have an Adoption Index
>     of at least two. (This takes precedence over any Rule requiring a
>     lower AI for such a proposal.)

Remove the leading quote. "A Proposal containing a VOC Directive has
[better than 'must have'] an Adoption Index of 2, or greater than 2
if another Rule requires it. This Rule takes precedence over any
Rule requiring a lower AI for such a Proposal." [Precedence relations
have as their relata Rules, not bits of Rules.]

>
>     A VOC Directive must unambiguously specify an Official Document
>     of Agora Nomic or a list of such Documents.  These Documents must
>     fit the following criteria:

"Each Document must fit the following criteria at the commencement of
the Voting Period of the Proposal containing the VOC Directive:"
[Simplifies what follows, since 3 of the 5 conditions have this
qualification. Also, you need to treat the Documents individually, 
and say what happens if a Document referred to in a VOC does not
meet the criteria. See below.]

>          i) They are required to be produced and/or maintained by
>             the Rules.
>         ii) They are not currently subject to a Claim of Error. (COE)
>             (when the VOC directive was proposed.)
>        iii) They are not currently subject to a CFJ, or an appeal
>             of a CFJ. (when the VOC was proposed.)

This may need to be tailored to fit with Kelly's Judicial Reform package.
Also, I'd say "...currently the subject of a CFJ...", but that's just
a quibble.

>         iv) The information within the Documents is currently in force,
>             and has not been superseded by a subsequent Document. (when
>             the VOC was proposed.)

Simpler just to say: "The information within the Document has not been
superceded by the subsequent publication of another Document." [Note
the switch to the singular.]

>          v) The Document is not the Ruleset. The Ruleset is
>             specifically excluded from all VOC Directives.

At this point, you must specify what happens if a Document in a VOC
fails to meet the criteria. You have two choices: invalidate the
entire VOC, including the effects of other Documents which do meet
the criteria, or just invalidate the VOC in that Document. Obviously
the latter is preferable. It's probably a good idea to introduce 
another definition at the top of the proto defining validity and
invalidity of VOCs.

>      Passage of a VOC Directive conforms the Game State to what it
>      would be if the Documents listed within the VOC Directive were
>      completely true and accurate at the Time they were produced (ie.
>      the State of the Game becomes that within the listed Documents,
>      plus all subsequent legal changes between the Time of the Document
>      and adoption of the VOC.)

Don't capitalize 'time'. Yecch! It's probably more accurate to refer
to the time the Document was first published in the Public Forum,
rather than just the "time they were produced", which is not as clear.
Still, this is the heart of the proto - and it's pretty good.

>      If another Document is issued during the voting period that does
>      not contradict the Documents in a passing VOC Directive it does
>      not alter the effects of a VOC Directive.

I'm astonished that a man as mad keen as you are about Rampant
Capitalization, hasn't capitalized 'Voting Period'. Also, "published 
in the Public Forum" is more accurate than "issued". Which reminds
me, we really should adopt a Rule defining "publication" as "publication
in the Public Forum".

>      If another Document is issued during the voting period that *does*
>      contradict the Documents in a passing VOC Directive, the Game
>      State is only changed if there is a COE alleging that the
>      contradiction is in fact an Error, and the Claim is admitted.

This is a little unclear. What if the Claim is still unsettled when
the VOC is adopted? Naturally, I'd also prefer it if you didn't
preempt my use of the word 'Error', and I absolutely insist that
you don't capitalize it, since it isn't defined anywhere else in the
Rules.

>      If, during the VOC Directive's Voting period, a COE is issued on a
>      Document within it, *and* the COE is admitted before passage, then
>      passage of the VOC Directive will have no effect on the Game

"passage...has no effect" [Clearer than "will have".] Also, "Voting
Period".

>      State.  A COE may not be admitted over any Document within a VOC
>      Directive *after* the Directive Passes.  (Passage means the
>      documents are not in error.)  This takes precedence over other
>      Rules dealing with COEs.

"This Rule takes precedence..." [See remarks above.]

>
>      All Game State changes due to a VOC Directive occur upon passage.
>      A VOC Directive does not have retroactive effects.
>
>      Documents within a successful VOC are true and accurate, and
>      the Game States they reference may not be modified prior to the
>      Time they were produced, even to reflect a prior mistake,
>      retracted move, or an Injunction.  This takes precedence over any
>      rule that would allow retroactive alterations or corrections to
>      the Game State after a VOC directive is adopted.
>
>      In no way does a VOC Directive invalidate, reverse, alter or
>      cancel any prior moves or transfers, even unrecorded or overlooked
>      ones.  A VOC Directive *only* adjusts the actual Game State to
>      conform to that perceived by the Players and Officers in Official
>      Documentation.

"to that reported in Official Documents."

Still needs work, but the idea is good.

