Kelly Martin was heard to say:
> 
> Wes> A piece of paper is an Entity, right? It is obviously a piece of
> Wes> paper, and has an individual existance. It's right here. Now I
> Wes> tear the piece of paper in half. Wow. Now there are two pieces of
> Wes> paper. Both would be Entities, right? Now let's say I tape those
> Wes> pieces of paper back togther, so it's one piece of paper again.
> Wes> It's still an Entity. Why wouldn't it be?
> 
> Wes> How is this different than the divisibility of Marks or Points?
> 
> because the piece of paper you end up with afterwards is clearly
> distinguishable from the piece of paper you started with.  after all,
> it has a tear down the middle, and tape holding it together, both
> characteristics it did not have when you started.  but if i take a
> Mark, divide it up into 100 elements of 0.01 Mark each, and then bring
> them back together, i can't tell the resulting Mark apart from the
> Mark i started with, or, for that matter, from any other Mark.

So you admit that a piece of paper is an entity? That's an important
step. 

The next step would be to compare it all to a car. A car is an entity,
right? It exists quite nicely. See that car over there? It has definite,
individual existance. It's a car. Now pop the hood (gee, I hope it's
your car... <grin>). See that little hose down there? It exists by
itself, too, right? It's a hose. It's an entity which is part of a
larger entity, the car. 

Now let's say the hose gets a hole in it. We take it to the auto shop
and they put in a new hose. The car is still an entity, and for all
intents and purposes it is the same entity. Yes, it is technically
slightly different. It has a new hose. It's a car with a new hose
instead of a car with an old hose. But would you go to your friends and
say "I have a new car!"?? Of course not. You don't have a new car, just
the old car with a new hose. It's still the same entity: the old car. 

Now even if you broke down that car into component parts and spread it
all over the place; hell, even if you sold your tires to one guy and
your engine block to someone else, if you accumulate all the parts
together again and reassemble it, it's still the same car. You might
have to go buy your engine block back from the guy you sold it to, but
if you did, you could put together your old car. 

But wait! You can't get that new hose back, so you go buy (another) new
one. Does that make this a different car? Did one hose make it a
different car before? Of course not. It's the same car, with a new hose.


Now, what would you say is wrong with this scenerio? 


Enjoy!

---
Wes Contreras      "Nonsense. You're only saying that because no one ever has."
wesc@magika.com                                          - Westley

