Status: RO

>> One, perhaps The, main point of us Platonist Nomic Players is that The
>> True Agora Gamestate _does_ have independent existence outside of people's
>> opinion. 
>> 
>Does not the power to create imply the power to destroy? If the
>Game State was created by consensus, it can be destroyed thus,
>if they simply cease to play (as opposed to all deregistering)

Ah, but that *doesn't* destroy the Game State!!  Consider the following:

All Players, simultaneously, cease to play, without deregistering.

Two years later, a person named Bob comes across some reference
to Agora Nomic.  Being interested, he does some digging, finds
records of Agora, and is able to determine the Game State at
the point that everyone ceased to play.

He now posts to the Public Forum that he registers as a Player.  Note
that such a message is sufficient for registration, without any
action on the part of any other Player.

Then he alleges that the Speaker has abandoned, and calls for the
Speaker to announce eir presence.  When the Speaker does not respond,
Bob becomes the Arbiter of Succession for Speaker Transfer.  Bob
is the only person to express a willingness to be Speaker, and thus
e becomes Speaker.

Bob now alleges that all other players are deregistered due to inactivity.
When the Registrar does not respond, the duty devolves to the Speaker
and Speaker Bob confirms that all Players except himself are
deregistered.  Now all offices are vacant and Bob fulfills the
duties of all officers.  Later, some of Bob's friends can join
and fill various offices.

Result: Agora Nomic continues, despite the fact that all Players
had ceased to play for two years.  In light of this, how can you
say that the Game State ceased to exist?

Chuck

