"Don" == Don Blaheta <blahedo@quincy.edu> writes:

>> Familiar, no. Aware of such a concept, yes. But I'd like in turn to
>> point out to you that the Rules define no such thing as anti-
>> Currencies. I'd say this notion is at the very best no more common-
>> sensical than my own interpretation of 1472.

Don> "Anticurrencies"?  And you're trying to say this is more obvious
Don> than the standard arithmetical concept of negativity?  You're
Don> batty.

"anticurrencies" are exactly equivalent to the standard concept of
negativity, as far as i'm concerned.

Don> Heh.  Really, it's not _that_ complex.  You just take the middle
Don> value, which is (arguably) easier than taking the arithmetic
Don> mean...  Apparently I was not the only Player to think so,
Don> either: only Swann opposed, although Kelly and Michael abstained.

actually, finding the median is more complicated than finding the
mean.  for the mean, you can just blindly add and divide.  for the
median, you have to sort.  well, you don't _have_ to sort; there are
algorithms to find the median of a collection without first sorting
it, but they're more complicated than they're worth.

k.
