Kelly Martin was heard to say:
> 
> Wes> The next step would be to compare it all to a car. A car is an
> Wes> entity, right? It exists quite nicely. See that car over there?
> Wes> It has definite, individual existance. It's a car. Now pop the
> Wes> hood (gee, I hope it's your car... <grin>). See that little hose
> Wes> down there? It exists by itself, too, right? It's a hose. It's an
> Wes> entity which is part of a larger entity, the car.
> 
> none of this is particularily controversial.  however, i now take the
> opportunity to point out that cars, and parts of cars, are very
> distinct from Marks in a very significant way: cars have physical
> existence.  Marks do not.  this fundamental difference places a great
> deal of strain on your analogy.

Not really. After all, having a physical manifestation of form is only 
one property which an entity may possess. 

> interesting scenario.  i feel obliged to point out that because in
> fact it is apparently not always so clear when a car's identity
> changes that we have seen fit to legislate into law what defines a
> car's identity.  specifically, the law attaches the identity of a car
> to its frame (and to its vehicle identification number, which is a
> property of that frame).  you can strip a car down to its frame and
> build a whole "new" car out of different parts on top of that frame,
> and yet under the law it is the same car you started with.  on the
> other hand, if you strip a car down to its frame, saving all the
> parts, obtain another compatible frame, and rebuild the car on the new
> frame, under the law it is _not_ the same car that you started with.
> now, why has our society chosen to establish this seemingly arbitrary
> standard?  i posit it is because it would otherwise be, at times, too
> difficult to determine whether or not a given car is the same car as
> another (previously existing) car.  

And in Nomic, we have determined that all Currencies (including Marks)
are Entities. "A Currency is a type of Nomic Entity" [Rule 1467/1]. However,
regardless of the legal definition, even if you built a whole new car on
the same frame, you would tell your friends that you built a new car.
You may mention that it has the same frame, but there are very few
people who would point to the Title and say "Oh, no, that's the same car
I used to have..." when talking in a normal social situation. 

> in part, this is because identity over temporal distance is not a
> black-and-white issue.  in the real world, everything is constantly
> changing.  i am not composed of the same set of atoms i was composed
> of a year ago.  there are, no doubt, some common atoms between the two
> sets, but many--perhaps most--of them have been replaced with "new"
> ones since.  it is virtually assured that i am now comprised of none
> of the atoms from the original zygote from which i sprang nearly 27
> years ago.  but this does not compromise my identity, or at least we
> don't tend to believe it does.  on the other hand, we often say things
> like "i'm not the person i was five years ago", which suggests that we
> do consider our identities to slowly (or, sometimes, not so slowly)
> change over time.

To use the new Nomic terminology that seems to be forming, your
Properties change over time, but your dasein does not. We are attempting
to reference the dasein of an Entity with our definitions. 

> however, in a theoretical construct such as the world of Agora, we
> need not worry about the constant physical processes that go on around
> us all the tiem in the real world.  things in Agora are infinitely
> simpler, infinitely cleaner.  and making analogies into a theoretical
> world from the real world is thus extremely suspect, because of the
> total lack of commonality in the nature of how things exists, and
> especially persist.  thus, i reject your argument as irrelevant.

What? Go over that once again? You are rejecting the common English use
of a term and definition because it may have been formed differantly if
Real Life were more like Nomic? We're missing something here... 

We are attempting to show that a Mark can be an Entity in spite of the
fact that it can be broken into pieces by attempting to show that the
word entity can refer to a collection of similar or related items rather
than solely to the component parts which make up that set. You reject
that argument because in Nomic, things are simpler? 



Enjoy!

