Laurent Bossavit was heard to say:
> 
> > As kelly points out, when we need a consistent rule (as in
> > laws about cars), we pick some arbitrary rule that _is_
> > consistent, but doesn't always agree with our intuitions,
> > like "if it has the same frame, it's the same car".  For
> > the purposes of Agora, we do need some consistent notion
> > of entitihood and identity, and that implies, again, that
> > it'll have to be a notion that doesn't entirely agree
> > with our intuitions.
> 
> Assuming, of course, that it is possible to give a definition of 
> Entity that is at the same time consistent in all case and neither a 
> gross oversimplification (like "All capitalized nouns in the RS 
> denote Entities") or an overspecialization (like "Only those things 
> specifically defined by other Rules as Entities are Entities").

What is an Entity? The only problem is that Kelly insists that the
normal Enlish definition of the word "entity" itself is not sufficient,
although she has no better suggestions for that function. 


Enjoy!

