"Wes" == Wes Contreras <magika@teleport.com> writes:

Wes> So you're saying that it's okay to make things illegal which will
Wes> happen anyways? In the beginning Agora Nomic, that sort of Rule
Wes> would be considered a Paradox and would end the Game, giving a
Wes> Win to whoever pointed it out.

well, that would be plain wrong, now, wouldn't it?  such an
interpretation stupidly assumes that legality and possibility are
somehow equivalent (or, rather, that illegality implies
impossibility).

it's legal, in most places, to levitate objects in the town square.
this doesn't make it possible.  in fact, it is rare that an impossible
act is made illegal, because doing so is a waste of time.  laws
generally only regulate possible behaviors.  this is, by the way, why
lesbianism has never been illegal in the UK: Queen Victoria refused to
admit the possibility of gay women, and thus refused to allow a law
making it illegal on the grounds that it was impossible.

any Rule that seeks to regulate (as opposed to describe) must
inherently admit to being broken.  this is no paradox.

k.
--
kelly martin                                 <kelly@poverty.bloomington.in.us>

