Wes sez:

> Does it matter? The point was to show that a component to an Entity
> can be removed and/or replaced while it still remains the "same" Entity.
> At some point, it would become a new Entity, but at what point that
> would be is not the issue. At what point would a Mark become a different
> Mark as pieces of it are broken off and replaced by pieces of different
> Marks? Who cares? A Mark is a Mark. 

What some of us are trying to say (i.e. Kelly, Chuck and me, unless 
I'm mistaken) is that a Mark does not exist in and of itself. You can 
transfer, for instance, 1/2+1/4+1/8+...+1/N**2 Marks, with 
arbitrary N; the result is a 1-Mark transfer because of the MUQ of 
Marks, but this particular Mark has indefinitely many "components". 
In short, a Mark is not a Mark, it's an abstraction.
---**---
Morendil

